{"term": "2011", "caseName": "Miller v. Alabama", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2011/10-9646", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - March 20, 2012", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/21929", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll hear argument first this morning in Case 10-9646, Miller v. Alabama.", "start": 0, "stop": 6.504, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "Mr. Stevenson.", "start": 6.504, "stop": 8.537, "duration": 2.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 8.537, "stop": 11.808, "duration": 3.27}, {"text": "In Graham v. Florida, this Court recognized that children are inherently characterized by internal attributes and external circumstances that preclude a finding of a degree of culpability that would make a sentence of life imprisonment without the possibility of parole constitutionally permissible under the Court's Eighth Amendment excessiveness analysis.", "start": 11.808, "stop": 34.504, "duration": 22.7}, {"text": "While the issue in Graham involved juveniles that were convicted of non-homicide offenses, these deficits in maturity and judgment and decisionmaking are not crime-specific.", "start": 34.504, "stop": 45.629, "duration": 11.13}, {"text": "All children are encumbered with the same barriers that this Court has found to be constitutionally relevant before imposition of a sentence of life imprisonment without parole or the death penalty.", "start": 45.629, "stop": 57.603, "duration": 11.97}, {"text": "In fact, in Roper, this Court acknowledged that these differences between children and adults exist even in the cases involving the most aggravated murders.", "start": 57.603, "stop": 67.575, "duration": 9.97}, {"text": "These deficits, these differences, are even more pronounced in young children.", "start": 67.575, "stop": 72.796, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Stevenson, but in Roper, the Court also made the point -- when it ruled out the death penalty, it said,", "start": 72.796, "stop": 87.972, "duration": 15.18}, {"text": "\"To the extent the juvenile death penalty might have residual deterrent effect, it is worth noting that the punishment of life imprisonment without the possibility of parole is itself a severe sanction. \"", "start": 87.972, "stop": 101.966, "duration": 13.99}, {"text": "So, the Court in Roper seemed to be anticipating this case and suggesting that -- that it was all right, it was constitutional.", "start": 101.966, "stop": 113.789, "duration": 11.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "There's no question, Justice Ginsburg, that the -- the default sentence in Roper was life imprisonment without parole, but we actually think that, specifically with regard to that provision, there is no greater deterrent effect, and these deficits, that these problems that children experience, lend themselves to an analysis that is subject when the punishment is life imprisonment without parole.", "start": 113.789, "stop": 137.655, "duration": 23.87}, {"text": "Like the death penalty--", "start": 137.655, "stop": 138.907, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about 50 years?", "start": 138.907, "stop": 140.191, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "Is that -- is that too much?", "start": 140.191, "stop": 141.859, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--What the Court held in -- in Graham--", "start": 141.859, "stop": 144.242, "duration": 2.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you know, once -- once you depart from the principle that we've enunciated that death is different, why is life without parole categorically different from 60 years or 70 years or -- you know, you'd be back here next term with a 60-year sentence?", "start": 144.242, "stop": 166.241, "duration": 22}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Scalia, I think you're absolutely right, that there is a point at which a term of year sentence could constitute the same kind of judgment--", "start": 166.241, "stop": 173.745, "duration": 7.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 173.745, "stop": 174.247, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--as life imprisonment without parole.", "start": 174.247, "stop": 175.547, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Good.", "start": 175.547, "stop": 175.98, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there is a distinction obviously between life imprisonment without parole and any other term sentence.", "start": 175.98, "stop": 181.851, "duration": 5.87}, {"text": "Those sentences in most instances, if the sentence is not too extreme, do permit the possibility of release.", "start": 181.851, "stop": 187.321, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "And what this Court held in Graham is not that the State forfeits the ability to incarcerate for life--", "start": 187.321, "stop": 193.658, "duration": 6.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll change my -- I'll change my question to 50 years without possibility of parole.", "start": 193.658, "stop": 200.229, "duration": 6.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 200.229, "stop": 200.829, "duration": 0.6}, {"text": "And--", "start": 200.829, "stop": 201.612, "duration": 0.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then you have no -- no distinction, right?", "start": 201.612, "stop": 203.781, "duration": 2.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I think there, it would be a tough case.", "start": 203.781, "stop": 206.716, "duration": 2.94}, {"text": "I think imposed on a juvenile, a 50-year sentence--", "start": 206.716, "stop": 209.518, "duration": 2.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Without--", "start": 209.518, "stop": 210.051, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--would not create the meaningful possibility of release that this Court ordered in the Graham context.", "start": 210.051, "stop": 215.072, "duration": 5.02}, {"text": "It would be right on the line, but I think 50 years would actually be on the other side of a meaningful possibility of release.", "start": 215.072, "stop": 220.975, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "It would be sort of a cynical reaction, if this Court were to say we ban life without parole for these kinds of offenders, it would be somewhat problematic to suggest that we're going to get as close to death as possible and then facilitate some kind of review.", "start": 220.975, "stop": 232.95, "duration": 11.97}, {"text": "I think what we're interested in--", "start": 232.95, "stop": 233.95, "duration": 1}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--How about 15 years old?", "start": 233.95, "stop": 235.216, "duration": 1.27}, {"text": "15, 60 years; or 14, 70 years?", "start": 235.216, "stop": 239.62, "duration": 4.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think all of the--", "start": 239.62, "stop": 240.67, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "What -- what's the distinction between 14 and 15?", "start": 240.67, "stop": 243.422, "duration": 2.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I think from a sentencing perspective, all of those sentences would be problematic.", "start": 243.422, "stop": 247.96, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "But the distinction between a 14-year-old and a 15-year-old for constitutional purposes that, of course, the younger you are, the more compelling are these deficits, these distinctions, that--", "start": 247.96, "stop": 257.582, "duration": 9.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand, but how are we -- how are we to know where to draw those lines?", "start": 257.582, "stop": 261.218, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "We can't do it on the basis of any historical tradition, certainly.", "start": 261.218, "stop": 265.587, "duration": 4.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I think that--", "start": 265.587, "stop": 266.837, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "The common law left it up to the jury to take account of the youthfulness of the offender.", "start": 266.837, "stop": 272.091, "duration": 5.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, what I think--", "start": 272.091, "stop": 273.275, "duration": 1.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "They're all entitled to jury trial, right, before their--", "start": 273.275, "stop": 276.56, "duration": 3.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, that's true.", "start": 276.56, "stop": 277.662, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "But of course in this case, Justice Scalia, and in the other case, there was no discretion for the sentence.", "start": 277.662, "stop": 281.881, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "Neither the judge nor the jury could give any effect to the age of Evan Miller, who was 14.", "start": 281.881, "stop": 286.435, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "But I also think that we've identified lots of laws that make these distinctions.", "start": 286.435, "stop": 291.153, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "We do provide for greater responsibilities--", "start": 291.153, "stop": 293.772, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would that satisfy you if the -- if it were not a mandatory term and it was left to the trier to put -- put in all the mitigating circumstances?", "start": 293.772, "stop": 305.162, "duration": 11.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That would not satisfy me, Justice Ginsburg, for all the reasons that this Court acknowledged in Graham.", "start": 305.162, "stop": 309.966, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "That -- that the problem with many of these crimes is that the offense itself can overwhelm all of these mitigating factors, all of these aspects of juvenile decisionmaking that we think are constitutionally permissible.", "start": 309.966, "stop": 325.393, "duration": 15.43}, {"text": "The other problem is that we still can't make good judgments about whether a child -- whether these characteristics are transitory or permanent.", "start": 325.393, "stop": 333.232, "duration": 7.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, you're saying it would be unprincipled for us to say -- or at least unsupported for us to say -- that the sentence cannot be mandatory, but that in some cases, it might still be imposed.", "start": 333.232, "stop": 347.323, "duration": 14.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it would be principled to -- to kind of strike down mandatory sentences, but I think constitutionally what this Court has recognized in Roper and in Graham, that it would be a -- a mistake to equate kids with adults.", "start": 347.323, "stop": 360.733, "duration": 13.41}, {"text": "And we don't have the ability to make those judgments even if we create a different kind of process.", "start": 360.733, "stop": 365.201, "duration": 4.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Even--", "start": 365.201, "stop": 365.703, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you take that off the table, then you leave us with nothing but saying that the sentence is never permitted or that it's always permitted.", "start": 365.703, "stop": 374.993, "duration": 9.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I don't mean to take it off the table; I just mean to argue, as we did previously, that a categorical ban would be consistent with the Court's understanding about child status and development.", "start": 374.993, "stop": 386.131, "duration": 11.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you could write the opinion for us, what would you hold?", "start": 386.131, "stop": 388.833, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would hold that children are categorically prohibited from being subjected to sentences--", "start": 388.833, "stop": 394.637, "duration": 5.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's -- what's the definition of a child for that purpose?", "start": 394.637, "stop": 397.172, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, we've presented data in this case that would exclude a youth 14 and younger.", "start": 397.172, "stop": 402.41, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "No State that has set a minimum age for life without parole has set it beneath the age of 15, other than one.", "start": 402.41, "stop": 408.714, "duration": 6.3}, {"text": "And so, we -- we would make that holding.", "start": 408.714, "stop": 410.232, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "I do think it would be--", "start": 410.232, "stop": 411.349, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, you -- you would hold you can't -- there cannot be a sentence of life imprisonment without parole for anyone under 15, but for anybody over 15, it would be permissible.", "start": 411.349, "stop": 420.872, "duration": 9.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No, I would also hold, Your Honor, that a mandatory sentence for that cohort would also be in violation of this Eighth Amendment principle.", "start": 420.872, "stop": 429.46, "duration": 8.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you could say you reserve that question for another day.", "start": 429.46, "stop": 432.512, "duration": 3.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that the problem, Justice Ginsburg, is -- is that these cases with the mandatory sentencing aspects to them create kind of a data issue that this Court has usually relied on to kind of generate an interest.", "start": 432.512, "stop": 444.903, "duration": 12.39}, {"text": "I think right now, we know that excluding considerations of age and character in a sentencing determination of life imprisonment without parole is problematic.", "start": 444.903, "stop": 455.711, "duration": 10.81}, {"text": "The Court in--", "start": 455.711, "stop": 456.478, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can you tell us where the age line needs to be drawn for constitutional purposes?", "start": 456.478, "stop": 460.832, "duration": 4.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I -- I would draw it at 18, Justice Alito, because we've done that previously; we've done that consistently.", "start": 460.832, "stop": 467.502, "duration": 6.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's where you think the logic of your argument leads.", "start": 467.502, "stop": 469.704, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's exactly right.", "start": 469.704, "stop": 470.787, "duration": 1.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you would say that a 17 -- a person of 17 years and 10 months, 11 months, who commits the worst possible string of offenses still -- and demonstrates great maturity -- still cannot be sentenced to life imprisonment without parole.", "start": 470.787, "stop": 487.832, "duration": 17.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right, for the same reasons that we made that determination in Graham and that the Court made that determination in Roper.", "start": 487.832, "stop": 493.586, "duration": 5.75}, {"text": "I understand that there are some tensions when we draw those kinds of lines--", "start": 493.586, "stop": 496.272, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry.", "start": 496.272, "stop": 496.655, "duration": 0.38}, {"text": "I thought you just said a second earlier that you had a bifurcated rule: No life without parole whatsoever for 15 and under, and no mandatory life for 16 -- 15 and over.", "start": 496.655, "stop": 511.114, "duration": 14.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That -- that would be -- I'd have two rules, Justice Sotomayor.", "start": 511.114, "stop": 514.149, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "My preferred rule would be a categorical ban on all juveniles under the age of 18.", "start": 514.149, "stop": 518.451, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "And I don't want to retreat from that in any way.", "start": 518.451, "stop": 520.303, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "All of these deficits, all of these characteristics, that we're talking about have been recognized to apply to all youth up until the age of 18.", "start": 520.303, "stop": 527.491, "duration": 7.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you -- how do you write the opinion to do the bifurcated rule?", "start": 527.491, "stop": 531.595, "duration": 4.1}, {"text": "What justifies an absolute ban at a certain age and a modified ban above an age, and how do you deal with Harmelin with respect to the second part of your rule--", "start": 531.595, "stop": 546.02, "duration": 14.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 546.02, "stop": 546.537, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--if Harmelin says we don't look at individualized sentencing?", "start": 546.537, "stop": 550.006, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "So, how do we get rid of the mandatory if that's what we're were going to do?", "start": 550.006, "stop": 553.624, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's a challenge, and I -- and I concede that.", "start": 553.624, "stop": 555.56, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "But I -- so, the first part of my answer would be that I think the easier rule to write would be that there is a categorical ban on all life without parole sentences for all children up until the age of 18, acknowledging--", "start": 555.56, "stop": 566.684, "duration": 11.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--How -- how do I come to that decision?", "start": 566.684, "stop": 568.251, "duration": 1.57}, {"text": "What do I -- just consult my own preferences on this matter?", "start": 568.251, "stop": 572.522, "duration": 4.27}, {"text": "Something like 39 States allow it.", "start": 572.522, "stop": 575.374, "duration": 2.85}, {"text": "I mean, the American people, you know, have decided that that's the rule.", "start": 575.374, "stop": 580.876, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "They allow it.", "start": 580.876, "stop": 581.794, "duration": 0.92}, {"text": "And the Federal government allows it.", "start": 581.794, "stop": 583.528, "duration": 1.73}, {"text": "So, I'm supposed to impose my -- my judgment on -- on what seems to be a consensus of the American people?", "start": 583.528, "stop": 592.249, "duration": 8.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, at least in this case, you'd look to your precedent in Roper and in Graham, which drew that line.", "start": 592.249, "stop": 597.737, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's not going to help me, you know.", "start": 597.737, "stop": 599.339, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand--", "start": 599.339, "stop": 600.222, "duration": 0.88}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 600.222, "stop": 601.589, "duration": 1.37}, {"text": "I understand, Justice Scalia, but I don't think you can draw much comfort in the fact that 39 jurisdictions make this theoretically possible.", "start": 601.589, "stop": 607.945, "duration": 6.36}, {"text": "That same number existed in the Graham context.", "start": 607.945, "stop": 610.161, "duration": 2.22}, {"text": "Most of those jurisdictions have not addressed a minimum age for life without parole.", "start": 610.161, "stop": 614.849, "duration": 4.69}, {"text": "In fact--", "start": 614.849, "stop": 615.599, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What do you mean when you say that, that they have not addressed it?", "start": 615.599, "stop": 617.884, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "If State law allows it, have they not addressed it?", "start": 617.884, "stop": 621.703, "duration": 3.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 621.703, "stop": 623.038, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "That is, what the State permits is that--", "start": 623.038, "stop": 624.805, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, legislators don't understand that their law permits this?", "start": 624.805, "stop": 627.94, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I don't think we can read into a transfer judgment, which is the only judgment that they've made.", "start": 627.94, "stop": 633.493, "duration": 5.55}, {"text": "They've said that some children of some age can be treated like adults.", "start": 633.493, "stop": 636.545, "duration": 3.05}, {"text": "They haven't talked about what that -- what the punishment should be.", "start": 636.545, "stop": 639.747, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "And the reason why I say that, Justice Alito, is that in many of these States, there's no minimum age for trying a child as an adult.", "start": 639.747, "stop": 645.818, "duration": 6.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I don't really understand this argument.", "start": 645.818, "stop": 647.753, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "You mean the legislatures have enacted these laws, but they don't realize that, under these laws, a -- a person under the age of 18 may be sentenced to life imprisonment without parole for -- for murder.", "start": 647.753, "stop": 660.411, "duration": 12.66}, {"text": "They don't understand that?", "start": 660.411, "stop": 661.611, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "They -- they have not considered that or adopted or endorsed it, would be more accurate.", "start": 661.611, "stop": 666.231, "duration": 4.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's difficult because the statistics show there are 2,300 prisoners now under sentence of -- with life without parole for juvenile murders and they're -- that were committed under 18.", "start": 666.231, "stop": 682.507, "duration": 16.28}, {"text": "2,300 nationwide.", "start": 682.507, "stop": 683.692, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that's correct.", "start": 683.692, "stop": 684.459, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, it's very difficult to assess your answer to Justice Alito that, oh, the legislatures don't know about this.", "start": 684.459, "stop": 692.548, "duration": 8.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in -- that answer -- that number, Your Honor, is partly rooted in the fact that these sentences are mandatory.", "start": 692.548, "stop": 698.352, "duration": 5.8}, {"text": "There is no one capable, once the court makes a decision to try the child as an adult, to do anything to consider the status of children.", "start": 698.352, "stop": 705.606, "duration": 7.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Stevenson--", "start": 705.606, "stop": 706.792, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you think these legislators don't understand what their laws provide, why don't you contact them?", "start": 706.792, "stop": 710.409, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "And when they -- when you tell them, do you realize that in your State a -- a 16-year-old or a 17-year-old may be sentenced to life in prison without parole for murder, they'll say: Oh, my gosh, I never realized that.", "start": 710.409, "stop": 721.717, "duration": 11.31}, {"text": "Let's change the law.", "start": 721.717, "stop": 722.767, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I mean, I don't think there are any legislatures that are -- that are quick to make their sentences less -- more compassionate, more responsive to -- to juvenile crime of any sort.", "start": 722.767, "stop": 732.94, "duration": 10.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, they've made a decision on this.", "start": 732.94, "stop": 734.709, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "Now maybe it's a bad decision--", "start": 734.709, "stop": 736.125, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 736.125, "stop": 736.661, "duration": 0.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--but I really don't understand how you can argue that they have not made a decision on this--", "start": 736.661, "stop": 742.465, "duration": 5.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think--", "start": 742.465, "stop": 742.998, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and they are not aware of what their law provides.", "start": 742.998, "stop": 745.167, "duration": 2.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 745.167, "stop": 745.55, "duration": 0.38}, {"text": "I think the strength of my argument, Justice Alito, is that the States that have actually considered, discussed, and passed laws setting a minimum age for life without parole have all set that minimum age above 15.", "start": 745.55, "stop": 758.757, "duration": 13.21}, {"text": "That's my primary argument.", "start": 758.757, "stop": 760.342, "duration": 1.59}, {"text": "Thirteen States have done it; all of them except for one have set it at 18--", "start": 760.342, "stop": 765.161, "duration": 4.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you think there is a difference between the State that says expressly a juvenile below a certain age may be sentenced to life imprisonment without parole and a State that says that if a person is convicted of capital murder, that sentence may be imposed and, in another -- in another provision, says that juveniles may be transferred for prosecution as adults.", "start": 765.161, "stop": 787.077, "duration": 21.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I--", "start": 787.077, "stop": 787.494, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "There's a difference between those two?", "start": 787.494, "stop": 788.594, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--There is.", "start": 788.594, "stop": 789.244, "duration": 0.65}, {"text": "And that's because the -- the transfer question, which is what informs whether children can be subject to these sentences or not, is a very different question.", "start": 789.244, "stop": 796.199, "duration": 6.95}, {"text": "It's a question about whether the juvenile system that may mandate release at age 18 or age 21 is adequate for an offender.", "start": 796.199, "stop": 803.969, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "It's not a judgment that that child should therefore be subject to life imprisonment without parole.", "start": 803.969, "stop": 809.607, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "And so, you have this disconnect.", "start": 809.607, "stop": 811.392, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "You have transfer judgments, which this Court recognized in Thompson and in Graham were not proxies for sentencing judgments.", "start": 811.392, "stop": 817.779, "duration": 6.39}, {"text": "And because of that, it is a very different calculation.", "start": 817.779, "stop": 820.565, "duration": 2.79}, {"text": "The second point is that if there is no minimum age for trying children as adults or even prosecuting children as adults, I think we'd have to concede that there is an age at which a life without parole sentence would be constitutionally impermissible for any crime.", "start": 820.565, "stop": 835.924, "duration": 15.36}, {"text": "And to the extent that the State hasn't addressed that, which they clearly haven't -- you know, in this cohort of 79 children with life without parole for crimes at 14 and younger, more than half come from States where there's no minimum age for trying children as adults.", "start": 835.924, "stop": 849.084, "duration": 13.16}, {"text": "That means in that State, a 10-year-old child would arguably have been contemplated by the legislature to be an appropriate person for life without parole, or an 8-year-old child and a 6-year-old child, and I think that asks too much of these statutes.", "start": 849.084, "stop": 861.558, "duration": 12.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Counsel, there is no question that you're dealing with a much smaller universe of children sentenced to life without parole who are 14 and under.", "start": 861.558, "stop": 872.432, "duration": 10.87}, {"text": "There's an argument that that's because so few of them commit the crimes.", "start": 872.432, "stop": 876.067, "duration": 3.63}, {"text": "But putting that aside, the universe is rather small.", "start": 876.067, "stop": 878.519, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 878.519, "stop": 879.203, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right?", "start": 879.203, "stop": 879.736, "duration": 0.53}, {"text": "There is a much, much larger group, as Justice Kennedy pointed out, for life without parole for juveniles at 15 and above.", "start": 879.736, "stop": 888.975, "duration": 9.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 888.975, "stop": 889.525, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Go back to my question.", "start": 889.525, "stop": 891.127, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 891.127, "stop": 891.511, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I need an answer to it.", "start": 891.511, "stop": 892.044, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 892.044, "stop": 892.561, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which is, assuming--", "start": 892.561, "stop": 894.129, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 894.129, "stop": 894.529, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--the bifurcated theory that you proffered, tell me how we get around Harmelin.", "start": 894.529, "stop": 901.467, "duration": 6.94}, {"text": "How would you write that decision?", "start": 901.467, "stop": 902.885, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 902.885, "stop": 903.335, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "Well, I think that, first of all, what this Court has relied on when it has looked at these numbers, what it has been trying to figure out, are these objective indicia of society's standards, its mores, its decency meter, if you will.", "start": 903.335, "stop": 915.959, "duration": 12.62}, {"text": "And we've looked at these numbers to inform us, are these sentences that are -- that are consistent with evolving standards of decency, or are they now beyond a maturing society?", "start": 915.959, "stop": 924.315, "duration": 8.36}, {"text": "And we've always found in these data some measures.", "start": 924.315, "stop": 927.534, "duration": 3.22}, {"text": "In the death penalty context, we've looked at that in the Roper area, in the Atkins area, and we've been able to make some judgments.", "start": 927.534, "stop": 933.604, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "The reason why we could do it in these death penalty cases is that unlike the cases here, the death penalty determination is discretionary.", "start": 933.604, "stop": 941.527, "duration": 7.92}, {"text": "The sentencer is required to consider and evaluate a range of mitigating circumstances and facts, including age, that help us assess whether the determination that death is the appropriate punishment means something in a society still trying to evolve.", "start": 941.527, "stop": 956.369, "duration": 14.84}, {"text": "Here that's not true.", "start": 956.369, "stop": 957.519, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "The majority of these sentences are mandatory.", "start": 957.519, "stop": 959.988, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "So, the number tells us less about what the Constitution requires--", "start": 959.988, "stop": 964.792, "duration": 4.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Mr. Stevenson, do you have statistics about how many of these sentences are imposed in under 18-year-olds in nonmandatory States?", "start": 964.792, "stop": 972.548, "duration": 7.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The -- the data on the larger population is not as precise, Justice Kagan, as it is with our younger population, but the majority of States are mandatory States, and the estimates are about that 85 percent of those sentences are mandatory sentences.", "start": 972.548, "stop": 988.325, "duration": 15.78}, {"text": "Certainly, the States that have the largest populations -- Michigan, Pennsylvania -- these States have mandatory regimes.", "start": 988.325, "stop": 995.745, "duration": 7.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, you think it would be true, going up to age 18, that 80-plus percent are imposed in States that have mandatory systems?", "start": 995.745, "stop": 1003, "duration": 7.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that's correct.", "start": 1003, "stop": 1003.667, "duration": 0.67}, {"text": "And, in fact, the overwhelming majority of those sentences come from a handful of States where there is very little discretion to impose a sentence other than life imprisonment without parole.", "start": 1003.667, "stop": 1014.042, "duration": 10.38}, {"text": "And because of that feature, I don't think, Justice Sotomayor, that the -- that the reliance on the number is quite as powerful here as it has been in the death penalty context, where that number represented a very communal judgment with a lot of factors.", "start": 1014.042, "stop": 1028.802, "duration": 14.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "There wasn't a majority in theory in Harmelin, and -- but at least three Justices spoke about a gross disproportionality.", "start": 1028.802, "stop": 1036.756, "duration": 7.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1036.756, "stop": 1037.757, "duration": 1}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it your views that life -- a mandatory life without parole for someone like a juvenile is grossly disproportionate?", "start": 1037.757, "stop": 1045.844, "duration": 8.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is, for the very reasons that the Court articulates in both Roper and Graham.", "start": 1045.844, "stop": 1050.831, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "We're not arguing that life without parole is disproportionate to the crime of aggravated murder.", "start": 1050.831, "stop": 1055.802, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "We're arguing that the status of children, with all of the deficits that childhood status creates, make that kind of judgment cruel.", "start": 1055.802, "stop": 1063.656, "duration": 7.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "If we can focus on the mandatory aspects of the case, I think -- I know you'd prefer a more general rule -- it may be that we have to have your general rule.", "start": 1063.656, "stop": 1075.364, "duration": 11.71}, {"text": "I'm not sure.", "start": 1075.364, "stop": 1076.215, "duration": 0.85}, {"text": "If I'm the trial judge, and I have to determine whether or not I'm going to give life without parole, and it's discretionary, what -- what do I look at?", "start": 1076.215, "stop": 1087.338, "duration": 11.12}, {"text": "Are -- can I get social scientists to come in and tell me what the chances of rehabilitation are?", "start": 1087.338, "stop": 1092.742, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "Are there -- are there statistics?", "start": 1092.742, "stop": 1095.194, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "Now, we have some quite compelling stories of rehabilitation in this case.", "start": 1095.194, "stop": 1099.814, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "I don't know if they're isolated; I don't know where they are in the statistical universe of how often rehabilitation is -- is demonstrated and is real.", "start": 1099.814, "stop": 1108.168, "duration": 8.35}, {"text": "What do I look at?", "start": 1108.168, "stop": 1109.037, "duration": 0.87}, {"text": "What's a judge supposed to do?", "start": 1109.037, "stop": 1110.904, "duration": 1.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think one of the problems, Your Honor, with -- with trying to make these judgments is that -- that even psychologists say that we can't make good long-term judgments about the rehabilitation and -- and transitory character of these young people.", "start": 1110.904, "stop": 1124.796, "duration": 13.89}, {"text": "That's the reason why in Graham this Court didn't permit that kind of discretion.", "start": 1124.796, "stop": 1128.348, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "We know that--", "start": 1128.348, "stop": 1129, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I thought that modern penology has abandoned that rehabilitation thing, and they -- they no longer call prisons reformatories or -- or whatever, and punishment is the -- is the criterion now.", "start": 1129, "stop": 1144.343, "duration": 15.34}, {"text": "Deserved punishment for crime.", "start": 1144.343, "stop": 1146.41, "duration": 2.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well--", "start": 1146.41, "stop": 1146.895, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, if that's the criterion, is everything that you say irrelevant?", "start": 1146.895, "stop": 1152.783, "duration": 5.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I--", "start": 1152.783, "stop": 1153.916, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let's assume I don't believe in rehabilitation, as I think sentencing authorities nowadays do not.", "start": 1153.916, "stop": 1161.638, "duration": 7.72}, {"text": "Both at the Federal and the State levels, it's been made clear.", "start": 1161.638, "stop": 1164.606, "duration": 2.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I -- I -- no.", "start": 1164.606, "stop": 1166.856, "duration": 2.25}, {"text": "I think it would still be relevant, Justice Scalia, but -- but I also don't think that correctional facilities have identified themselves as having no role to play in the rehabilitative process.", "start": 1166.856, "stop": 1176.914, "duration": 10.06}, {"text": "I mean, one of the problems with this sentence of life imprisonment without parole is that it actually bans and shields this population from a whole range of services that are specifically designed to rehabilitate: education services, treatment services, anger management programs.", "start": 1176.914, "stop": 1190.908, "duration": 13.99}, {"text": "All of these programs exist within prisons, including the Federal prisons, because we do care how people perform when they are released.", "start": 1190.908, "stop": 1197.661, "duration": 6.75}, {"text": "And so, corrections is still very much the heart and soul of what we do.", "start": 1197.661, "stop": 1200.779, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "But even if it wasn't, punishment nonetheless has to be proportionate, and recognize that it can be excessive.", "start": 1200.779, "stop": 1208.952, "duration": 8.17}, {"text": "And what this Court has said is that when you're looking at children, to equate the failings of a child and an adult would be cruel.", "start": 1208.952, "stop": 1215.189, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "It would be unfair to -- given our knowledge and understanding of what developmental science has taught us and what we know about kids.", "start": 1215.189, "stop": 1222.377, "duration": 7.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, again, it seems you're just forcing us into a -- a bipolar position.", "start": 1222.377, "stop": 1229.031, "duration": 6.65}, {"text": "We're either going to say that you can't prevail at all or that everyone under 18 is -- cannot get life without parole.", "start": 1229.031, "stop": 1237.803, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "I don't see this middle course--", "start": 1237.803, "stop": 1240.088, "duration": 2.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1240.088, "stop": 1240.604, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--which you seem to have abandoned, and you can't tell me how a judge would apply it if we -- if we chose not to abandon it.", "start": 1240.604, "stop": 1245.308, "duration": 4.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I don't intend to abandon it, Justice Kennedy.", "start": 1245.308, "stop": 1248.094, "duration": 2.79}, {"text": "I mean, obviously, I'm arguing for this categorical ban, but I think the Court could obviously do something else.", "start": 1248.094, "stop": 1252.312, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "We think that there is a basis for concluding, unquestionably, that a child under the age of 15 should not be exposed to life without parole based on this Court's precedents and on the data that's presented.", "start": 1252.312, "stop": 1263.354, "duration": 11.04}, {"text": "The Court could set a categorical line there and, at the same time, make a determination that subjecting any child under the age of 18 to life without parole where there is no ability to consider age is fundamentally at odds with what this Court has now constitutionally recognized in both Roper and Graham.", "start": 1263.354, "stop": 1281.648, "duration": 18.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Stevenson, may I ask you a case -- a question specifically about the Miller case?", "start": 1281.648, "stop": 1288.069, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "There were two boys involved in this horrendous crime.", "start": 1288.069, "stop": 1292.054, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "The older one took a plea and got life with parole.", "start": 1292.054, "stop": 1297.858, "duration": 5.8}, {"text": "Was the plea offered to Miller?", "start": 1297.858, "stop": 1300.643, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No plea was offered to Miller.", "start": 1300.643, "stop": 1302.745, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "The -- what tends to happen, and there was some evidence of this that was developed earlier, is that the question was who was going to give a statement first, who was the most cooperative, whose lawyer is most effective at accomplishing that.", "start": 1302.745, "stop": 1317.339, "duration": 14.59}, {"text": "There were some complaints.", "start": 1317.339, "stop": 1318.805, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "There's a postconviction pending now that makes some allegations about what the lawyer didn't do to facilitate a plea.", "start": 1318.805, "stop": 1324.858, "duration": 6.05}, {"text": "But, no, there was no offer of life with parole made to Evan Miller.", "start": 1324.858, "stop": 1329.829, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "And one of the difficulties, of course, in these cases is that, you know, the younger you are, the more vulnerable you are, the less experienced you are, and the less capable you are of managing these dynamics in the criminal justice system that sometimes can be very outcome-determinative.", "start": 1329.829, "stop": 1344.172, "duration": 14.34}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Any idea how many juveniles subject to a sentence of life without parole do plead to a lesser sentence?", "start": 1344.172, "stop": 1353.945, "duration": 9.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, no, it's very hard to determine, mostly because states don't keep data--", "start": 1353.945, "stop": 1360.182, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1360.182, "stop": 1360.765, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--on the issue.", "start": 1360.765, "stop": 1361.198, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any reason, just -- I realize it's speculation, but wouldn't you think prosecutors would view that as a particularly attractive offer to someone who's young in the sense that they may regard the sentence as extraordinary themselves, that it may be particularly attractive to someone who's young in a way that it wouldn't be a 40-year-old, a -- an offer of 25 years may not be as attractive as it is to a 15-year-old?", "start": 1361.198, "stop": 1390.034, "duration": 28.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they might.", "start": 1390.034, "stop": 1391.517, "duration": 1.48}, {"text": "And I would concede, Your Honor, that this population is kind of less equipped to make determinations about whether to take a plea or whether to not take a plea than an adult.", "start": 1391.517, "stop": 1400.673, "duration": 9.16}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It might be also a basis for -- to question the statistics you put forward about how often--", "start": 1400.673, "stop": 1406.327, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1406.327, "stop": 1406.961, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--this sentence is actually imposed.", "start": 1406.961, "stop": 1408.929, "duration": 1.97}, {"text": "In other words, the evolving standards of decency you suggest -- the prosecutors in the state may not be immune to that evolution, either.", "start": 1408.929, "stop": 1416.935, "duration": 8.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "They may not be, Your Honor, but we haven't found sort of -- at least in this population, any evidence that they are capable of protecting children who, we believe at least, should be protected.", "start": 1416.935, "stop": 1426.807, "duration": 9.87}, {"text": "And one of the interesting things at least looking at this cohort of 79, a great number of them have older codefendants.", "start": 1426.807, "stop": 1433.144, "duration": 6.34}, {"text": "Both of the kids in the cases before the Court today have older codefendants who got sentences that were less than life without parole.", "start": 1433.144, "stop": 1440.3, "duration": 7.16}, {"text": "In the Kuntrell Jackson case--", "start": 1440.3, "stop": 1441.734, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but those statistics aren't very helpful because we have no idea in the particular cases as to whether or not perhaps the older offender was less -- less guilty than the 16-, 17-, 15-year-old.", "start": 1441.734, "stop": 1453.125, "duration": 11.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That -- that's right.", "start": 1453.125, "stop": 1454.125, "duration": 1}, {"text": "Although in some of these cases when you read the opinions, you do see the evidence of the shooter not getting the life without parole sentence and the accomplice getting it.", "start": 1454.125, "stop": 1461.231, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "And I guess my point would be is that--", "start": 1461.231, "stop": 1462.764, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "That happened in Jackson.", "start": 1462.764, "stop": 1463.997, "duration": 1.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, it did.", "start": 1463.997, "stop": 1464.533, "duration": 0.54}, {"text": "Yes, it did.", "start": 1464.533, "stop": 1465.316, "duration": 0.78}, {"text": "And my point would be that it -- this younger population is going to be disadvantaged in managing this aspect of the process that I think is quite important when the Court is trying to consider whether there should be a categorical ban or something less than a categorical ban.", "start": 1465.316, "stop": 1481.977, "duration": 16.66}, {"text": "And, Justice Kennedy, I don't mean to suggest that the Court cannot, consistent with its precedents, make a categorical ban under 17.", "start": 1481.977, "stop": 1490.916, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "But I also don't mean to suggest that if the Court can't do that, that there aren't ways of reconciling the precedents, drawing a line at 15 and striking down mandatory life without parole.", "start": 1490.916, "stop": 1500.789, "duration": 9.87}, {"text": "I would urge, for the reasons that we've stated, that in these circumstances it's better to have a sentence where you can make a judgment about rehabilitation and public safety later in life.", "start": 1500.789, "stop": 1512.78, "duration": 11.99}, {"text": "We're not arguing that the State has to give away the authority to incarcerate someone even for the rest of their life -- life without parole, which is available in this State, Alabama, would facilitate that, but creates a meaningful possibility of release that this Court has ordered to be constitutionally necessary in Graham v. Florida.", "start": 1512.78, "stop": 1530.491, "duration": 17.71}, {"text": "I see my white light is on.", "start": 1530.491, "stop": 1531.825, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "I'll reserve the rest of my time for rebuttal.", "start": 1531.825, "stop": 1533.343, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Stevenson.", "start": 1533.343, "stop": 1534.177, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "Mr. Neiman.", "start": 1534.177, "stop": 1545.401, "duration": 11.22}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 1545.401, "stop": 1550.205, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "Imposing life without parole sentences on aggravated murder offenders like Evan Miller is in line with the national consensus, is morally justified, and is consistent with legitimate penological goals.", "start": 1550.205, "stop": 1561.929, "duration": 11.72}, {"text": "I'd like to touch on all three of those points at some juncture today if I can, but I'd like to start if I can with the conversation Mr. Stevenson was having with a few of the Justices about the national consensus issue in this case and more particularly what we can infer about the judgment of legislatures and ultimately the people based on the statutes we have in this case and the very different set of circumstances we're looking at here then the circumstances the Court was looking at in Graham.", "start": 1561.929, "stop": 1587.412, "duration": 25.48}, {"text": "Exhibit A on that front is the fact that out of the 39 States or jurisdictions that allow this--", "start": 1587.412, "stop": 1595.001, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "sentence, as Mr. Stevens has indicated -- or Mr. Stevenson has indicated, a good chunk of them, 27 in all, make the sentence the minimum sentence under the statute.", "start": 1595.001, "stop": 1604.456, "duration": 9.45}, {"text": "That's an important fact both because it tells us a little bit about the retributive goals that the legislatures were trying to achieve through these statutes, but it also--", "start": 1604.456, "stop": 1613.562, "duration": 9.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Life without parole is the minimum?", "start": 1613.562, "stop": 1615.664, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Life without parole is the minimum sentence for anyone who commits an aggravated murder or at least certain kinds of aggravated murders in 27 of those jurisdictions.", "start": 1615.664, "stop": 1624.353, "duration": 8.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's also -- that's also the maximum because there could be no death penalty.", "start": 1624.353, "stop": 1627.222, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "For a juvenile, yes, Justice Kennedy, that's correct.", "start": 1627.222, "stop": 1629.741, "duration": 2.52}, {"text": "And effectively the message that the legislatures are sending is that with respect to aggravated murders, the worst of the worst kinds of murders, there are effectively two sentences.", "start": 1629.741, "stop": 1640.547, "duration": 10.81}, {"text": "There is either the death penalty or there is some sort of mitigating circumstance.", "start": 1640.547, "stop": 1645.683, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "The person is at least going to serve life without parole in order to--", "start": 1645.683, "stop": 1649.652, "duration": 3.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Of the numbers, the 79 to 82 -- I guess there's some disagreement whether it's 82 or 79.", "start": 1649.652, "stop": 1656.658, "duration": 7.01}, {"text": "Regardless, in your opinion, or maybe it's in the briefs, I just can't remember it, of those, say, 79, how many are there for reasons of mandatory sentence where they would not -- no one could consider the individualized nature of the crime or the criminal?", "start": 1656.658, "stop": 1674.37, "duration": 17.71}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--We don't have precise statistics, sir.", "start": 1674.37, "stop": 1677.472, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "I should say I--", "start": 1677.472, "stop": 1678.138, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's your estimate?", "start": 1678.138, "stop": 1678.905, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I can't vouch to the statistics on that point.", "start": 1678.905, "stop": 1681.024, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's all right.", "start": 1681.024, "stop": 1681.424, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "What's your estimate?", "start": 1681.424, "stop": 1682.357, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "My answer is I don't know, in terms of how many are mandatory and how many are not.", "start": 1682.357, "stop": 1688.612, "duration": 6.26}, {"text": "Mr. Stevenson--", "start": 1688.612, "stop": 1689.379, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, how many come from the States that have this mandatory system?", "start": 1689.379, "stop": 1692.664, "duration": 3.29}, {"text": "That shouldn't be too hard to find out.", "start": 1692.664, "stop": 1694.599, "duration": 1.93}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, overall, Mr. Stevenson cited about 8 who were sentenced pursuant to non-mandatory schemes of the 79 to 82.", "start": 1694.599, "stop": 1703.722, "duration": 9.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Non-mandatory.", "start": 1703.722, "stop": 1704.239, "duration": 0.52}, {"text": "So--", "start": 1704.239, "stop": 1704.672, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Correct.", "start": 1704.672, "stop": 1705.055, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--So, you think it's almost -- it's probably percent.", "start": 1705.055, "stop": 1708.274, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "According to Mr. Stevenson's statistics, it's about 90 percent of the cohort that comes from the mandatory jurisdiction.", "start": 1708.274, "stop": 1715.53, "duration": 7.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that's -- all right.", "start": 1715.53, "stop": 1716.18, "duration": 0.65}, {"text": "It's about 70 or 71, and I remember reading a statistic somewhere where they managed to count up the number of possibilities, i.e., serious murders committed by those under 15 over 50 years or some long number of years, and it was somewhere in the 70,000s, what was it?", "start": 1716.18, "stop": 1735.341, "duration": 19.16}, {"text": "Or 20,000s?", "start": 1735.341, "stop": 1736.01, "duration": 0.67}, {"text": "What was it?", "start": 1736.01, "stop": 1736.676, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, the statistics I have seen that Mr. Stevenson cited in his reply brief had 7500--", "start": 1736.676, "stop": 1742.264, "duration": 5.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Seventy-five hundred?", "start": 1742.264, "stop": 1743.197, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--as the number of arrests of persons under the age of 15 for committing homicide or non-negligent manslaughter.", "start": 1743.197, "stop": 1749.434, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll read it.", "start": 1749.434, "stop": 1750.251, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that--", "start": 1750.251, "stop": 1751.02, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's about 1 percent.", "start": 1751.02, "stop": 1752.32, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It--", "start": 1752.32, "stop": 1753.236, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "One percent.", "start": 1753.236, "stop": 1754.072, "duration": 0.84}, {"text": "If I carry that number around in my mind, that 1 percent of those who might have obtained this terrible penalty, 1 percent are actually given it?", "start": 1754.072, "stop": 1766.729, "duration": 12.66}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Your Honor, as Graham indicated, that denominator is crucial.", "start": 1766.729, "stop": 1771.266, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "But the 7500 number cannot be the appropriate denominator for determining whether actual sentencing practices indicate a national consensus against this practice.", "start": 1771.266, "stop": 1780.289, "duration": 9.02}, {"text": "The reason why is because that 7500 number is not the number of convictions; it's not the number of opportunities that judges would have had to impose this sentence.", "start": 1780.289, "stop": 1788.309, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "It is the number of arrests.", "start": 1788.309, "stop": 1789.995, "duration": 1.69}, {"text": "And it's the number of arrests over the course of 40 years in every jurisdiction, including those that don't impose life without parole at all.", "start": 1789.995, "stop": 1796.665, "duration": 6.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I see.", "start": 1796.665, "stop": 1797.182, "duration": 0.52}, {"text": "All right.", "start": 1797.182, "stop": 1797.599, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Counsel--", "start": 1797.599, "stop": 1797.917, "duration": 0.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's not even for homicide offenses that would qualify for life imprisonment without parole for an adult.", "start": 1797.917, "stop": 1805.255, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "It's for any non-negligent homicide; isn't that right?", "start": 1805.255, "stop": 1808.206, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, Justice Alito.", "start": 1808.206, "stop": 1809.306, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "And the real denominator here, the one the Court ought to look at when it considers the role that actual sentencing practices play in the analysis, ought to be the number of aggravated murder convictions.", "start": 1809.306, "stop": 1818.497, "duration": 9.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right, but what's the--", "start": 1818.497, "stop": 1819.53, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's a number we don't have.", "start": 1819.53, "stop": 1820.764, "duration": 1.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It must be easier to get to this, I guess, so I'll -- but I want to be sure you do at some point.", "start": 1820.764, "stop": 1824.318, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "And I'm not certain it's a cruel and unusual punishment argument.", "start": 1824.318, "stop": 1829.553, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "It may be more of a due process argument.", "start": 1829.553, "stop": 1831.922, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "But I want to know the justification -- given all those statistics that you've seen and that was in Roper and so forth, procedurally speaking, what is the justification for not giving the defendant any opportunity to point to mitigating features in his lack of development, in his age, in his upbringing, et cetera?", "start": 1831.922, "stop": 1854.17, "duration": 22.25}, {"text": "That to me is a difficult question, but before we get to that topic, I'd -- go ahead.", "start": 1854.17, "stop": 1858.472, "duration": 4.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Actually, I do want to ask, and it dovetails with what Justice Breyer is asking, the Edmund/Tison line for adults, which is we can't execute someone who hasn't killed, intended to kill or was reckless in killing.", "start": 1858.472, "stop": 1873.232, "duration": 14.76}, {"text": "This is a question more in the Jackson case, because I think it's an issue there.", "start": 1873.232, "stop": 1878.219, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "But although all murder is heinous and regrettable, there are different kinds of murder.", "start": 1878.219, "stop": 1885.307, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "That's why some people are subject to the death penalty and others are not.", "start": 1885.307, "stop": 1889.025, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "And I do see a world of difference between the Miller killing and the Jackson killing, vis-a -- vis, the individual defendants' personal liability.", "start": 1889.025, "stop": 1898.882, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "So, assuming there are different kinds of -- of killings -- of murder, should we be looking at the Edmund/Tison line at all?", "start": 1898.882, "stop": 1911.956, "duration": 13.07}, {"text": "Should we be talking about its application to juveniles in a different way?", "start": 1911.956, "stop": 1917.01, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "Edmund/Tison basically, okay, felony murder if you know that there's a gun involved, but should that line be the same for juveniles?", "start": 1917.01, "stop": 1928.083, "duration": 11.07}, {"text": "And, if so, then how do you go back to justifying, as Justice Breyer spoke about, the mandatory nature of life imprisonment without parole, given that not every juvenile is equal and not every murder is equal with respect to them?", "start": 1928.083, "stop": 1950.848, "duration": 22.76}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Sotomayor, the clearest line the Court could draw on this front would be the line that the Court initially set out in Graham as between homicide and non-homicide offenses.", "start": 1950.848, "stop": 1961.723, "duration": 10.88}, {"text": "Perhaps there would be some question about whether an Edmund type felony murder counts as a homicide offense or not, but my suggestion is that it would, at least if the Court is looking for a clear line that wouldn't undermine too much of what the Court set out in Graham in terms of clearly distinguishing between homicide and non-homicide offenders.", "start": 1961.723, "stop": 1980.184, "duration": 18.46}, {"text": "Nonetheless, I certainly agree that there are fundamental differences between certain kinds of murders, and I think that judgment is reflected in the legislation we have in at least 27 of these States, where aggravated murder in the very least carries with it a life without parole sentence for any defendant regardless of the mitigating circumstances.", "start": 1980.184, "stop": 2000.181, "duration": 20}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is not an individual legislative determination.", "start": 2000.181, "stop": 2002.533, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "That is -- that is just--", "start": 2002.533, "stop": 2004.883, "duration": 2.35}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is a legislative determination that aggravated murder as a class of offenses is so contrary to society's values, and so contrary to the dignity that we assume that every victim ought to be afforded, that life without parole is the appropriate sentence.", "start": 2004.883, "stop": 2022.027, "duration": 17.14}, {"text": "So I think there is an inference to be made there about the legislative judgment, particularly because the sentence is a minimum one.", "start": 2022.027, "stop": 2028.097, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "The three Justice concurrence, you mentioned, Justice Sotomayor, from Harmelin makes this point -- point quite vividly.", "start": 2028.097, "stop": 2034.601, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "In Solem v. Helm, the Court had struck down a sentence under the gross disproportionately analysis, and the Harmelin concurrence indicated that the Court was a little more comfortable doing that, because the sentence in that case was above the minimum, and thus, did not reflect the judgment of the legislature.", "start": 2034.601, "stop": 2049.095, "duration": 14.49}, {"text": "But when we are talking about the minimum sentence, it's fair to infer that that is the sentence that the legislature not as a class, in terms of a class of offenses, that would be the minimum appropriate sentence for that particular crime.", "start": 2049.095, "stop": 2061.502, "duration": 12.41}, {"text": "Now, Justice Breyer--", "start": 2061.502, "stop": 2062.168, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "When you -- it's a little confusing to me, but when you refer to \"minimum\", I assume that was because of the statutes prior to Graham had death as one of the other options, that that is no longer an option.", "start": 2062.168, "stop": 2075.01, "duration": 12.84}, {"text": "So it's -- it's a little awkward to refer to it as minimum when it's also the maximum.", "start": 2075.01, "stop": 2079.464, "duration": 4.45}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's correct, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 2079.464, "stop": 2082.166, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "When you have -- when an individual is prosecuted for an aggravated murder that carries this sentence, is it typical to also charge lesser included offenses?", "start": 2082.166, "stop": 2090.938, "duration": 8.77}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Mr. Chief Justice, and--", "start": 2090.938, "stop": 2093.374, "duration": 2.44}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And -- and in general, what is the distinction between exposure to the -- the maximum crime and a lesser included crime?", "start": 2093.374, "stop": 2103.179, "duration": 9.81}, {"text": "In other words, what is the difference between aggravated murder and manslaughter?", "start": 2103.179, "stop": 2108.483, "duration": 5.3}, {"text": "It typically turns on the state of mind, doesn't it?", "start": 2108.483, "stop": 2111.085, "duration": 2.6}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's correct, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 2111.085, "stop": 2112.835, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, is there any reason to think that juries in the case where they have the option for lesser included offenses might be concerned in light of the age of the defendant about whether or not the requisite intent was formed?", "start": 2112.835, "stop": 2126.945, "duration": 14.11}, {"text": "It seems to me that some of the issues that we have suggested justify a different treatment of juveniles have to do with mental development, and those same issues would be taken into account by a jury in considering which of a list of offenses the juvenile should be convicted of.", "start": 2126.945, "stop": 2145.439, "duration": 18.49}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, it is certainly within the realm of reason and possibility for--", "start": 2145.439, "stop": 2150.06, "duration": 4.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was it -- was it a factor in Miller's case?", "start": 2150.06, "stop": 2152.412, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "Was there a lesser -- lesser offense that was charged?", "start": 2152.412, "stop": 2157.064, "duration": 4.65}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, Justice Ginsburg, there were lesser included charges of at least felony murder which has a very different intent type element to it.", "start": 2157.064, "stop": 2167.772, "duration": 10.71}, {"text": "But Miller, at least with respect to the charge on capital murder committed in the course of arson which is an intentional murder was found guilty by the jury on that charge.", "start": 2167.772, "stop": 2176.71, "duration": 8.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "He was -- the -- there was also a felony murder charge in the Miller case?", "start": 2176.71, "stop": 2184.466, "duration": 7.76}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Justice Ginsburg, there were two felony murder charges, one as to the robbery in the case and one as to the arson in the case.", "start": 2184.466, "stop": 2193.572, "duration": 9.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "So -- so it may not be realistic to speak of mandatory life without parole.", "start": 2193.572, "stop": 2199.393, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "It's only mandatory if the youth is convicted of the highest charge brought, but it remains within the power of the jury, in light of the youth, to convict him of a lesser offense which would not produce mandatory life imprisonment without parole?", "start": 2199.393, "stop": 2216.937, "duration": 17.54}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I suppose that's so, Justice Scalia.", "start": 2216.937, "stop": 2219.404, "duration": 2.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are juries instructed that life without parole is a necessary consequence of their decision?", "start": 2219.404, "stop": 2225.741, "duration": 6.34}, {"text": "I suppose a defense attorney could argue it.", "start": 2225.741, "stop": 2229.526, "duration": 3.78}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Kennedy, actually, I think you are right to the extent you are suggesting that juries probably don't -- aren't actually instructed on that point.", "start": 2229.526, "stop": 2235.697, "duration": 6.17}, {"text": "In fact, it would probably be reversible error, I suppose--", "start": 2235.697, "stop": 2238.132, "duration": 2.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would think so.", "start": 2238.132, "stop": 2238.666, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--for a jury to be instructed on that point.", "start": 2238.666, "stop": 2240.668, "duration": 2}, {"text": "Nonetheless, the judgment that legislatures have reached in terms of setting life without parole as a floor for, you know, any murderer is one that was -- that is reasonable and justified and--", "start": 2240.668, "stop": 2251.29, "duration": 10.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Neiman, I wonder if we can go back to the issue that Justice Breyer left on the table, and this doesn't have much to do with how many States do what, but instead just to say that in the death penalty context, we have insisted on individualized sentencing.", "start": 2251.29, "stop": 2266.968, "duration": 15.68}, {"text": "And in Graham, of course, we equated juveniles who were sentenced to life without parole to people who -- to adults who were sentenced to death and said that those two should be treated equivalently.", "start": 2266.968, "stop": 2281.226, "duration": 14.26}, {"text": "And I'm wondering whether that doesn't suggest that the rules we have in the death penalty context about individualized sentencing ought to apply to juveniles who are sentenced to life without parole?", "start": 2281.226, "stop": 2294.551, "duration": 13.32}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Kagan--", "start": 2294.551, "stop": 2296.151, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Regardless of how many States do what and how many times this happened, but just, you know, two facts.", "start": 2296.151, "stop": 2301.722, "duration": 5.57}, {"text": "We have insisted on this in the death penalty context, and we have equated the death penalty context to juveniles without life -- parole in Graham.", "start": 2301.722, "stop": 2310.061, "duration": 8.34}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Kagan, the answer on that front, I think, is that Harmelin effectively sets a bright line here such a that individualized sentencing is only required in a -- in a death penalty case.", "start": 2310.061, "stop": 2322.553, "duration": 12.49}, {"text": "And it does so--", "start": 2322.553, "stop": 2323.488, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "But Harmelin is pre-Graham, and in Graham we equated these two things, adults sentenced to death and juveniles sentenced to life without parole.", "start": 2323.488, "stop": 2331.841, "duration": 8.35}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, the reason why Harmelin drew that line, and I guess more to the point, the reason why Woodson v. North Carolina and Lockett v. Ohio held that individualized sentencing was required in the death penalty context was not because the sentence happened to be the highest sentence that someone could receive, but because the sentence was death.", "start": 2331.841, "stop": 2348.286, "duration": 16.45}, {"text": "And there were certain--", "start": 2348.286, "stop": 2349.07, "duration": 0.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "In Graham, didn't the Court reject the idea of individualized sentencing in which youth would be taken into account on a case-by-case basis?", "start": 2349.07, "stop": 2355.959, "duration": 6.89}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's correct, Justice Alito.", "start": 2355.959, "stop": 2357.342, "duration": 1.38}, {"text": "The States were here jumping up and down asking for that precise result, and we did not get it.", "start": 2357.342, "stop": 2361.93, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "And the reason why, the result the Court thought was appropriate was rather than allowing the defendant to argue for mitigating circumstances and for the State to respond with aggravating circumstances in one of these cases, the answer was for the juvenile to get a mitigation trump card.", "start": 2361.93, "stop": 2376.522, "duration": 14.59}, {"text": "And in one of these sentencing proceedings, the juvenile would be able to say, I'm a juvenile, and that means that I don't get the highest sentence I otherwise would get.", "start": 2376.522, "stop": 2384.876, "duration": 8.35}, {"text": "I win the sentencing phase as -- as a matter of law.", "start": 2384.876, "stop": 2388.347, "duration": 3.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the fact that we said that individualized sentencing was not enough in one context does not suggest that individualized sentencing ought not to be the rule in a different context where there is no categorical bar.", "start": 2388.347, "stop": 2400.571, "duration": 12.22}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Kagan, the response on that front, I think, is that the rule from Woodson and Lockett requiring individualized sentencing was one that is specifically tailored to the unique aspects of the death penalty, aspects that remain unique, notwithstanding Graham and the rule it imposed with respect to juveniles.", "start": 2400.571, "stop": 2421.301, "duration": 20.73}, {"text": "But also Woodson and Lockett -- although I realize the premise of your question is that we should not look at what other States are doing, the premise of Woodson and Lockett was that States had widely rejected mandatory death penalty sentencing, and we know from the legislative record here that States have done quite the contrary when it comes to mandatory life without parole sentencing--", "start": 2421.301, "stop": 2442.065, "duration": 20.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "So is that -- I have -- I understand your arguments, both sides.", "start": 2442.065, "stop": 2445.617, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "I think I've pretty much gotten the arguments on the question of the individualized sentencing.", "start": 2445.617, "stop": 2451.853, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "You can make an argument that it should be individualized, life without parole up to age 18.", "start": 2451.853, "stop": 2457.574, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "Say 7 through 17, and there is an argument the other way which you are making, okay.", "start": 2457.574, "stop": 2462.042, "duration": 4.47}, {"text": "What I want to know is your argument the opposite way on this one.", "start": 2462.042, "stop": 2465.761, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "What's the minimum age, in your opinion, or is there any constitutional minimum at all in respect to which you could give for a murder a child life without parole?", "start": 2465.761, "stop": 2478.488, "duration": 12.73}, {"text": "I mean, you could have an instance of a 10-year-old or an 8-year-old.", "start": 2478.488, "stop": 2483.64, "duration": 5.15}, {"text": "I mean, is it totally up to the States, or is there a minimum?", "start": 2483.64, "stop": 2486.175, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "And if there is a minimum, what is it in your opinion.", "start": 2486.175, "stop": 2489.21, "duration": 3.03}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, Justice Breyer, I think there is a minimum now.", "start": 2489.21, "stop": 2492.412, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is it?", "start": 2492.412, "stop": 2492.945, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- I would be hesitant to commit to a minimum without--", "start": 2492.945, "stop": 2497.982, "duration": 5.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, do your best.", "start": 2497.982, "stop": 2498.732, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Without further factual development--", "start": 2498.732, "stop": 2499.751, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you want to say 12?", "start": 2499.751, "stop": 2500.801, "duration": 1.05}, {"text": "Do you want to say 10?", "start": 2500.801, "stop": 2501.851, "duration": 1.05}, {"text": "Do you want to say 9?", "start": 2501.851, "stop": 2502.936, "duration": 1.09}, {"text": "Because as soon as whatever you say, I'm going to say, 14> [\"]?", "start": 2502.936, "stop": 2506.405, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 2506.405, "stop": 2510.04, "duration": 3.63}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Okay.", "start": 2510.04, "stop": 2510.69, "duration": 0.65}, {"text": "I will say -- I would argue if I were the State up here trying to defend a 12-year-old sentence, I would argue that that was the line.", "start": 2510.69, "stop": 2518.979, "duration": 8.29}, {"text": "So a 12 -- well, no -- well, yes.", "start": 2518.979, "stop": 2521.598, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "Someone who's either--", "start": 2521.598, "stop": 2522.95, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you see the difficulty?", "start": 2522.95, "stop": 2523.583, "duration": 0.63}, {"text": "All right.", "start": 2523.583, "stop": 2524.017, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "So now put yourself in my position.", "start": 2524.017, "stop": 2525.719, "duration": 1.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I was beginning to agree with you about this case, because I thought you were appealing to what the American people think about the line or maybe to the common law, now that common law had a rule of the age of reason.", "start": 2525.719, "stop": 2543.261, "duration": 17.54}, {"text": "I think below 12, you couldn't -- at least you couldn't impose the death penalty.", "start": 2543.261, "stop": 2547.232, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "Maybe you couldn't even convict for a felony.", "start": 2547.232, "stop": 2549.334, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "But you just plucked some number out of the air.", "start": 2549.334, "stop": 2551.984, "duration": 2.65}, {"text": "Why can't I pluck one out of the air if you pluck one out of the air?", "start": 2551.984, "stop": 2555.488, "duration": 3.5}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Scalia, I was about to give Justice Breyer the arguments that I would make if I were the State in those circumstances about why that's the line.", "start": 2555.488, "stop": 2562.575, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "Reason number one is national consensus.", "start": 2562.575, "stop": 2564.177, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If we look to objective indicia, as all of the cases in this line have, what is the lowest age as to which you can say there is any indication of a societal consensus that this is okay?", "start": 2564.177, "stop": 2577.417, "duration": 13.24}, {"text": "Would it be 14?", "start": 2577.417, "stop": 2580.286, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well--", "start": 2580.286, "stop": 2582.155, "duration": 1.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many States allow it for a 13-year-old or a 12-year-old?", "start": 2582.155, "stop": 2585.773, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The number of States that allow it for a 12-year-old are somewhere around -- well, I suppose that number is close to 10 or so.", "start": 2585.773, "stop": 2597.148, "duration": 11.38}, {"text": "So that's one reason I would draw the line around 12 or so.", "start": 2597.148, "stop": 2600.033, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "If you look at, for example, the table--", "start": 2600.033, "stop": 2601.317, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "10 states will allow it for a 12-year-old.", "start": 2601.317, "stop": 2603.585, "duration": 2.27}, {"text": "How many would allow it for a 13-year-old?", "start": 2603.585, "stop": 2605.421, "duration": 1.84}, {"text": "Do you happen to know?", "start": 2605.421, "stop": 2606.254, "duration": 0.83}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--At that point, we are getting up to much more substantial numbers.", "start": 2606.254, "stop": 2611.173, "duration": 4.92}, {"text": "I guess when we get up to 14, we are somewhere in the realm of 30 or more.", "start": 2611.173, "stop": 2615.126, "duration": 3.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you take into account, when the -- the child is in the juvenile system initially, has to be moved to the adult system.", "start": 2615.126, "stop": 2624.415, "duration": 9.29}, {"text": "Is the judgment -- is there any cutoff on the transfer?", "start": 2624.415, "stop": 2631.319, "duration": 6.9}, {"text": "Or can a child be transferred to the adult system at any age?", "start": 2631.319, "stop": 2639.342, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that I think is the appropriate line in terms of thinking about what the minimum is here.", "start": 2639.342, "stop": 2644.979, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "The answer depends on the jurisdiction.", "start": 2644.979, "stop": 2646.079, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "In Alabama, 14 is the minimum.", "start": 2646.079, "stop": 2648.181, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "But that number is, compared to a lot of other jurisdictions, a little high.", "start": 2648.181, "stop": 2651.299, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if you are under 14, you can't be transferred out of the juvenile system?", "start": 2651.299, "stop": 2656.787, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 2656.787, "stop": 2657.237, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "In Alabama, if you are under 14, you can't be transferred out.", "start": 2657.237, "stop": 2659.57, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "Now, many other States, at age 13, you can be transferred in -- you can be transferred into the adult system which is why there are few 13-year-olds serving this sentence but--", "start": 2659.57, "stop": 2669.527, "duration": 9.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "If he were only 13, he would get out when?", "start": 2669.527, "stop": 2670.81, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "When he was 21?", "start": 2670.81, "stop": 2672.729, "duration": 1.92}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--In Alabama, the juvenile justice system's jurisdiction terminates at 21, yes.", "start": 2672.729, "stop": 2681.068, "duration": 8.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's why he is arguing that the legislatures don't focus on it.", "start": 2681.068, "stop": 2685.804, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "If you do a public opinion poll, or just ask me, for example, or ask anyone, you say the question is: Should -- at what age should juveniles be able to be transferred out of the juvenile system into the adult system?", "start": 2685.804, "stop": 2701.399, "duration": 15.59}, {"text": "You might get one answer.", "start": 2701.399, "stop": 2704.615, "duration": 3.22}, {"text": "Maybe 14, maybe 15, maybe 12.", "start": 2704.615, "stop": 2705.965, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "But if you put the question: At what age should they be receiving a mandatory life without parole, the answer might be different.", "start": 2705.965, "stop": 2713.47, "duration": 7.5}, {"text": "And his point is they never ask that question.", "start": 2713.47, "stop": 2716.588, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "They ask the first question; not the second.", "start": 2716.588, "stop": 2718.622, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "And that disturbs me enough to think that I can't think the answer to this question I asked you just relies on public opinion polls or even just the number of States.", "start": 2718.622, "stop": 2729.596, "duration": 10.97}, {"text": "I am not sure about it.", "start": 2729.596, "stop": 2731.348, "duration": 1.75}, {"text": "But that's why I want to hear your response, because it sounds like we are arguing between whether it should be 13, 12, or 14, in terms of an absolute cutoff.", "start": 2731.348, "stop": 2743.823, "duration": 12.47}, {"text": "So how do I approach that?", "start": 2743.823, "stop": 2745.223, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "I'm asking you for help on that one.", "start": 2745.223, "stop": 2746.875, "duration": 1.65}, {"text": "I know you have a side in this.", "start": 2746.875, "stop": 2748.542, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "But I say, well, we are talking about 14, and we have all this scientific literature and so forth.", "start": 2748.542, "stop": 2754.545, "duration": 6}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Breyer, the reason why it's fair to infer that legislatures would have concluded that a 14-year-old, for example, in Alabama would be subject to a mandatory life without parole sentence is precisely because it's mandatory.", "start": 2754.545, "stop": 2767.888, "duration": 13.34}, {"text": "Surely the legislatures understood that when they were transferring persons who committed crimes like aggravated murder that were well within the heartland of the crimes for which the transfer statutes were intended, those offenders would be subject to the minimum sentences at least.", "start": 2767.888, "stop": 2783.398, "duration": 15.51}, {"text": "It's quite another thing to say, well, the legislature might have enacted a statute providing for transfer for a 14-year-old; and for a non-homicide crime, they might have assumed that the person would get less than the maximum in terms of life without parole.", "start": 2783.398, "stop": 2794.872, "duration": 11.47}, {"text": "But surely the legislators understood that those offenders would at least get the minimum.", "start": 2794.872, "stop": 2799.076, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "And the reason the line is more safely drawn at 13 or 12, it's because if you look at, for example, the tables from the Department of Justice reports that both sides and the amici have cited listing the transfer ages, by and large, the number seems to be cut off at 12 or so.", "start": 2799.076, "stop": 2815.452, "duration": 16.38}, {"text": "And 12 would be on the very bottom of the range; and if I were a defense attorney, I would be arguing much harder for a line at 13 than 12.", "start": 2815.452, "stop": 2822.692, "duration": 7.24}, {"text": "I imagine if I were a defense attorney, I'd be arguing for an even higher line than that.", "start": 2822.692, "stop": 2826.077, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "But the point is that if we are going to judge this in terms of objective indicia of what society has decided, that seems to be the line that society has drawn.", "start": 2826.077, "stop": 2835.349, "duration": 9.27}, {"text": "That line--", "start": 2835.349, "stop": 2836.232, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the Petitioner's brief, the idea of deterrence kind of drops by the way side.", "start": 2836.232, "stop": 2841.753, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "Have there been any studies that show that there is a deterrence value?", "start": 2841.753, "stop": 2849.425, "duration": 7.67}, {"text": "I remember in Roper, there was actually discussion among the young people before they committed the crime as to whether or not they could get the penalty.", "start": 2849.425, "stop": 2857.363, "duration": 7.94}, {"text": "It was actually right there in the record.", "start": 2857.363, "stop": 2859.731, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "Does the State rely on the deterrence component of the punishment here?", "start": 2859.731, "stop": 2865.452, "duration": 5.72}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Kennedy, we think that deterrence is in the mix, but it's certainly not the primary goal that these statutes serve when--", "start": 2865.452, "stop": 2872.039, "duration": 6.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it retribution?", "start": 2872.039, "stop": 2873.14, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Retribution, Justice Kennedy, would be the primary goal, bringing society's retributive force to bear on those who commit the worst sort of crimes.", "start": 2873.14, "stop": 2880.228, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Retribution, of course, is related to personal culpability.", "start": 2880.228, "stop": 2882.913, "duration": 2.68}, {"text": "We said that in Tison, and that loops back into the minor problem.", "start": 2882.913, "stop": 2886.882, "duration": 3.97}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's exactly right, Justice Kennedy, but I think one point on which Mr. Miller and the State fundamentally disagree here is it what we can conclude about a juvenile's culpability when the juvenile has committed aggravated murder.", "start": 2886.882, "stop": 2899.19, "duration": 12.31}, {"text": "The reason why Graham came out as it did, the reason why life without parole was not permissible, was because Graham himself had not committed murder.", "start": 2899.19, "stop": 2907.896, "duration": 8.71}, {"text": "The Court there said that meant that Graham's culpability was twice diminished, once because he was a juvenile and once because he had not committed murder.", "start": 2907.896, "stop": 2915.551, "duration": 7.65}, {"text": "Well, here we have the hypothetical from Graham where the one level of diminishment is gone.", "start": 2915.551, "stop": 2920.605, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "And Miller has -- Miller is entitled to a one-level diminishment because of his juvenile status, but he is not entitled to that second level of diminishment which he is what he is seeking here.", "start": 2920.605, "stop": 2929.894, "duration": 9.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you aware of any statistics that give us some quantitative sense as to how many juveniles after years and years of prison show significant rehabilitation?", "start": 2929.894, "stop": 2941.785, "duration": 11.89}, {"text": "Do we know anything about that?", "start": 2941.785, "stop": 2943.019, "duration": 1.23}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Kennedy, I know of no statistics on that particular front.", "start": 2943.019, "stop": 2947.939, "duration": 4.92}, {"text": "I imagine that some vignettes could be told about success stories and some vignettes could be told about stories that were not success stories.", "start": 2947.939, "stop": 2955.611, "duration": 7.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you have any reason to think that juveniles are any better than anyone else as far as learning from prison is concerned?", "start": 2955.611, "stop": 2962.865, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "I mean, recidivism is a big problem, isn't it?", "start": 2962.865, "stop": 2966.334, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "People who have been to prison go out and commit the same crimes again, don't they?", "start": 2966.334, "stop": 2970.871, "duration": 4.54}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's exactly right, Justice Scalia.", "start": 2970.871, "stop": 2972.321, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any reason to think that juveniles are any different?", "start": 2972.321, "stop": 2974.756, "duration": 2.43}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Scalia, I haven't seen any studies that would suggest that juveniles do better, particularly when they are subjected to the sorts of crimes that I think everyone would have -- or the sorts of offenses, let me say, that I think everyone would agree the Constitution would have to permit a sentence of say 40 years minimum or the like.", "start": 2974.756, "stop": 2991.635, "duration": 16.88}, {"text": "So I just don't think -- I think society -- society's primary goal here or the Government's primary goal here is expressing the retributive judgment about the wrongfulness of murder and why it's different from, not homicide, but I think governments are quite legitimate and quite reasonable when they also say that they don't want to roll the dice on convicted murderers.", "start": 2991.635, "stop": 3010.362, "duration": 18.73}, {"text": "Society acts with particular revulsion when a convicted murderer commits a crime again.", "start": 3010.362, "stop": 3015.333, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "And even if -- and even if that difference in terms of recidivism is no different, or even if the possibility for recidivism is no different, the fact that the person committed a murder once and might commit a murder again is reason enough for legislatures to be hesitant to allow for parole in these circumstances.", "start": 3015.333, "stop": 3031.276, "duration": 15.94}, {"text": "With respect to the penological purposes, there's also an important purpose here with respect to the unique factors and the unique circumstances that murder victims and their families face.", "start": 3031.276, "stop": 3043.683, "duration": 12.41}, {"text": "I think a lot of people hear about life-without-parole sentences, and if they impose them on political grounds or policy-based grounds, one of their sort of pragmatic responses is, well, what's the cost to all this?", "start": 3043.683, "stop": 3056.577, "duration": 12.89}, {"text": "Why not just let these guys get their parole hearings, give them that hope, and likely they won't get parole anyway?", "start": 3056.577, "stop": 3062.914, "duration": 6.34}, {"text": "And there's really no cost to society at least in allowing that process to occur, but the cost is to the victims and their families who have to endure what are often very painful hearings and parole hearings.", "start": 3062.914, "stop": 3075.205, "duration": 12.29}, {"text": "And when those come up on a frequent basis, that sort of re-traumatization process is something that governments can legitimately take into account when they decide that for aggravated murder -- not for other crimes but for aggravated murder -- that a life-without-parole sentence is an appropriate sentence.", "start": 3075.205, "stop": 3092.1, "duration": 16.89}, {"text": "On the moral culpability point, there would be some anomalies created by the rule that Miller is seeking here.", "start": 3092.1, "stop": 3100.037, "duration": 7.94}, {"text": "Miller's asking the Court to effectively hold him in the same place in terms of his moral culpability as the defendant in Graham.", "start": 3100.037, "stop": 3108.976, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "In other words, Graham can only get life -- life with parole because of his reduced moral culpability.", "start": 3108.976, "stop": 3114.211, "duration": 5.23}, {"text": "And Miller is saying he should only get life without parole because of his reduced culpability.", "start": 3114.211, "stop": 3119.348, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "So that would mean one of two things: either the Eighth Amendment would put a murderer on the same moral level as someone who committed a non-homicide crime as in Graham; or Graham himself would be back in this Court or a court of another jurisdiction arguing that because Graham held that Graham himself had categorically less culpability than someone like Miller, then Graham himself is entitled to a lesser punishment than the one that Miller, in fact, received.", "start": 3119.348, "stop": 3148.867, "duration": 29.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "When you look at those two cases and you look at the individuals, the child's actions in the two cases, they really are remarkably similar.", "start": 3148.867, "stop": 3157.14, "duration": 8.27}, {"text": "They're sort of -- of a piece.", "start": 3157.14, "stop": 3158.44, "duration": 1.3}, {"text": "Don't you agree?", "start": 3158.44, "stop": 3159.924, "duration": 1.48}, {"text": "I mean, how is it that the child's actions in this case were any different from that in Graham?", "start": 3159.924, "stop": 3167.528, "duration": 7.6}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Kagan, I think that Miller's actions were dramatically different from Graham's actions; in part because Miller intended to kill this victim, and killed the victim in a rather gruesome way.", "start": 3167.528, "stop": 3180.838, "duration": 13.31}, {"text": "So there's not an element of luck here in terms of the fact that, oh, well, Graham was simply lucky that he didn't commit--", "start": 3180.838, "stop": 3187.842, "duration": 7}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's in -- in the Jackson case.", "start": 3187.842, "stop": 3189.278, "duration": 1.44}, {"text": "In the Jackson case, the crime was very similar to--", "start": 3189.278, "stop": 3192.13, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry.", "start": 3192.13, "stop": 3192.63, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "Justice Ginsburg is, of course, right.", "start": 3192.63, "stop": 3194.296, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I defer to my colleague from Arkansas in terms of the distinctions between Jackson and Graham, but certainly with respect to Miller's crime, his moral culpability is greater, and the law should recognize that.", "start": 3194.296, "stop": 3208.172, "duration": 13.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "If the judge were to determine under a -- a rule that the sentence can't be mandatory whether or not life should be imposed, what would be the sorts of factors that he would look at, or do you think that those are just too ineffable, too imprecise to be considered?", "start": 3208.172, "stop": 3225.467, "duration": 17.3}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Justice Kennedy, I think it certainly would be possible to have a regime under which a judge considered mitigating circumstances in a case like this.", "start": 3225.467, "stop": 3235.323, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "Many jurisdictions have reasonably opted for that route rather than the one that Alabama and 26 other jurisdictions have.", "start": 3235.323, "stop": 3241.561, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "They're just the standard sorts of mitigating circumstances that we see in capital cases and things?", "start": 3241.561, "stop": 3245.78, "duration": 4.22}]}, {"speakerName": "John C. Neiman Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Absolutely.", "start": 3245.78, "stop": 3246.297, "duration": 0.52}, {"text": "I think that's exactly what would happen.", "start": 3246.297, "stop": 3247.464, "duration": 1.17}, {"text": "You would have arguments about certain murders being worse than others.", "start": 3247.464, "stop": 3250.851, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "And Mr. Miller would have an opportunity to argue about other mitigating circumstances relating to his background and the like, as he's argued in his reply brief here.", "start": 3250.851, "stop": 3260.374, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "But at the same time, it's reasonable for legislatures to conclude that they're going to draw a line in the sand with respect to aggravated murder, such that -- as a floor in terms of the appropriate punishment, the defendant is going to get at the very least life without parole, a punishment that's no doubt severe but one that is less severe than the impact that the crime has had on society.", "start": 3260.374, "stop": 3285.172, "duration": 24.8}, {"text": "And for those reasons, we'd ask the Court to affirm.", "start": 3285.172, "stop": 3287.357, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Neiman.", "start": 3287.357, "stop": 3288.941, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "Mr. Stevenson, you have four minutes remaining.", "start": 3288.941, "stop": 3291.509, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 3291.509, "stop": 3292.845, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "I just want to make clear that the rule we seek would not require States to impose the same sentence on juveniles convicted of homicides from juveniles convicted of non-homicides.", "start": 3292.845, "stop": 3304.053, "duration": 11.21}, {"text": "The States would be free to do that if they chose to, but they could certainly create a regime where it's life with parole where there are different ages for eligibility.", "start": 3304.053, "stop": 3311.39, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "In fact, the State of Nevada makes you eligible for parole after 15 years if the crime is a non-homicide, 20 years if it's a homicide.", "start": 3311.39, "stop": 3319.663, "duration": 8.27}, {"text": "The States would still have a great deal of flexibility to create, consistent with this Court's rule, a regime that makes these distinctions.", "start": 3319.663, "stop": 3326.499, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "Justice Kennedy, I did want to point -- direct your attention to two amicus briefs that I think respond to two of the questions you've raised.", "start": 3326.499, "stop": 3332.32, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "There is an amicus brief submitted by criminologists in this case, and it looks specifically at the question of deterrence.", "start": 3332.32, "stop": 3337.374, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "And what they've found is life without parole has not had any measurable deterrent effect.", "start": 3337.374, "stop": 3342.261, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "The States that don't put juveniles -- don't subject children to life without parole have actually experienced the same level of decrease in violent crime and homicide as the States that do.", "start": 3342.261, "stop": 3352.384, "duration": 10.12}, {"text": "And in fact, in some of those jurisdictions, the decrease is even more significant.", "start": 3352.384, "stop": 3356.086, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "I also want to address your question, Justice Scalia.", "start": 3356.086, "stop": 3357.954, "duration": 1.87}, {"text": "There is -- there are some studies that have established that juveniles are more likely or less likely to recidivate after an intervention than adults.", "start": 3357.954, "stop": 3367.143, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "Generally speaking, homicide offenders are categorically less likely to recidivate than many non-homicide offenders.", "start": 3367.143, "stop": 3374.732, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "Drug offenders and property crime offenders are much more likely to recidivate than -- than homicide offenders.", "start": 3374.732, "stop": 3380.384, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "And so there's a lot to support that a judgment rooted in these penological concerns would be well-supported here.", "start": 3380.384, "stop": 3387.473, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "I also want to return, Justice Breyer, to your question.", "start": 3387.473, "stop": 3390.775, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "Mr. Neiman has -- argued that we can read into these statutes a commitment to imposing life without parole at a particular age, and that age is the age of transfer.", "start": 3390.775, "stop": 3400.031, "duration": 9.26}, {"text": "I just want to highlight that the two States with the largest populations of juveniles serving life without parole by a huge margin are Pennsylvania and Michigan, neither of which has a minimum age.", "start": 3400.031, "stop": 3411.687, "duration": 11.66}, {"text": "That means in those States, a child of any age can be subject to a mandatory sentence of life without parole.", "start": 3411.687, "stop": 3417.157, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "It's simply not true -- true that we can read into those statutes in those jurisdictions any kind of conscious commitment to thinking about age.", "start": 3417.157, "stop": 3425.162, "duration": 8}, {"text": "The other point I want to make--", "start": 3425.162, "stop": 3426.848, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you think the legislators in Pennsylvania and Michigan don't understand what their laws provide?", "start": 3426.848, "stop": 3431.5, "duration": 4.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I -- I think that they haven't thought about it.", "start": 3431.5, "stop": 3433.518, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "Yes, I do think that.", "start": 3433.518, "stop": 3434.535, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "I mean, for example -- this goes to the next point I was about to make -- my colleague keeps talking about aggravated murder.", "start": 3434.535, "stop": 3440.439, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "In the State of Pennsylvania, it's not just aggravated murder that subjects you to a mandatory life without parole; if you're convicted of second-degree murder -- no intent -- diminished -- it's still mandatory life without parole.", "start": 3440.439, "stop": 3451.578, "duration": 11.14}, {"text": "We have 14-year-old children -- and again, that's the largest cohort in our group -- in the State of Pennsylvania convicted of clearly unintentional killings that have been subject to mandatory life without parole.", "start": 3451.578, "stop": 3462.118, "duration": 10.54}, {"text": "South Dakota does the same thing.", "start": 3462.118, "stop": 3464.054, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "I think, where there is no minimum age and where you have that kind of regime, I cannot -- I don't think we can conclude that they've thought about, yes, it's appropriate--", "start": 3464.054, "stop": 3472.491, "duration": 8.44}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if they -- what if they do?", "start": 3472.491, "stop": 3473.41, "duration": 0.92}, {"text": "I mean, what if, after our decision or even after the argument, States go back and say, look, the decision is based on the fact that they don't think we know our law, that we haven't thought about it, so let's have a hearing about it, and then we vote that yes, there should be -- or no, there should not be a minimum age.", "start": 3473.41, "stop": 3487.936, "duration": 14.53}, {"text": "We think at 16, whatever age they do.", "start": 3487.936, "stop": 3491.122, "duration": 3.19}, {"text": "Then does the constitutional rule change?", "start": 3491.122, "stop": 3492.972, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 3492.972, "stop": 3493.574, "duration": 0.6}, {"text": "I--", "start": 3493.574, "stop": 3494.14, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Once we get 30 States saying, look, we've thought about it and this is our answer, then whether the Eighth Amendment prohibits it or not changes?", "start": 3494.14, "stop": 3500.577, "duration": 6.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No, I -- I don't think it changes, because there is an age at which this Court is obligated under the Eighth Amendment to say a sentence of this sort, a permanent judgment that life-long incarceration is -- is required--", "start": 3500.577, "stop": 3511.785, "duration": 11.21}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 3511.785, "stop": 3512.218, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "But one of the things we take into account is societal consensus, and you say we should ignore the 30 -- whatever it is -- States that allow this because they didn't really think about it.", "start": 3512.218, "stop": 3520.907, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "So I'm postulating let's make -- let's see if they have thought about it.", "start": 3520.907, "stop": 3523.943, "duration": 3.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 3523.943, "stop": 3524.443, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "Well, in -- in that regard, Justice -- Mr. Chief Justice, I think that we do have 13 States that have thought about it, that have expressly looked at this question of what the minimum age should be.", "start": 3524.443, "stop": 3533.982, "duration": 9.54}, {"text": "And in 12 of those 13 States that have set the age above 14, most of those States have set the age at 18.", "start": 3533.982, "stop": 3540.804, "duration": 6.82}, {"text": "So if that's the Court's lens, then I think that would support the kind of rule that we're seeking here--", "start": 3540.804, "stop": 3545.106, "duration": 4.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if, instead of striking down the laws in these States, why don't we just require the State legislatures to think about it, all right?", "start": 3545.106, "stop": 3553.878, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "And -- and then see how many think about it, and -- and come up with, you know, something that agrees with you or doesn't agree with you.", "start": 3553.878, "stop": 3560.366, "duration": 6.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I think that's in part--", "start": 3560.366, "stop": 3561.884, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Wouldn't that be more democratic somehow?", "start": 3561.884, "stop": 3563.451, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It might be more democratic, but I don't think it would be consistent with the constitutional obligation that this Court has to protect people who are vulnerable from excessive punishment.", "start": 3563.451, "stop": 3572.624, "duration": 9.17}, {"text": "And this is a cohort that we contend is the most vulnerable and should be shielded from this excessive punishment.", "start": 3572.624, "stop": 3577.577, "duration": 4.95}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Stevenson, Mr. Neiman.", "start": 3577.577, "stop": 3579.179, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 3579.179, "stop": 3580.012, "duration": 0.83}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - March 20, 2012", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/23578", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll hear argument next in Case 10-9647, Jackson v. Hobbs.", "start": 0, "stop": 8.104, "duration": 8.1}, {"text": "Welcome back.", "start": 8.104, "stop": 9.622, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 9.622, "stop": 11.272, "duration": 1.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 11.272, "stop": 13.574, "duration": 2.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You haven't changed your mind in the interim?", "start": 13.574, "stop": 15.61, "duration": 2.04}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 15.61, "stop": 18.045, "duration": 2.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No, Justice Scalia, I haven't.", "start": 18.045, "stop": 20.328, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "I do want to emphasize -- yes.", "start": 20.328, "stop": 23.547, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could you start -- I know that Enmund and Tison has to do with death eligibility with respect to adults, but it does draw a line between death eligibility with respect to intentionality or not, or recklessness.", "start": 23.547, "stop": 41.843, "duration": 18.3}, {"text": "Assuming for the sake of argument that some of us might be interested in whether a line should be created for juveniles who intended or didn't intend death, with respect to their eligibility for life without parole, whether it's mandatory or voluntary, how would we write that?", "start": 41.843, "stop": 67.809, "duration": 25.97}, {"text": "Would -- would we just import all the Enmund and Tison jurisprudence?", "start": 67.809, "stop": 72.113, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "Or would we say something different with respect to juveniles?", "start": 72.113, "stop": 75.998, "duration": 3.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I think you -- you could do that.", "start": 75.998, "stop": 78.35, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "In fact, in Graham, the Court makes these statements that they're trying to exempt and shield juveniles who did not kill, quote,", "start": 78.35, "stop": 87.205, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "\"or did not intend to kill. \"", "start": 87.205, "stop": 89.141, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "And that language could be a basis for organizing the Court's thinking on this issue.", "start": 89.141, "stop": 94.376, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "And, obviously, in this case where there wasn't a requirement of the specific intent to kill that was required in the Alabama case, that -- that might dictate a certain different outcome.", "start": 94.376, "stop": 105.001, "duration": 10.63}, {"text": "I think the challenge with that is that juvenile status, juvenile intent, is a much more complicated issue, and that for many of the same reasons that are problematic with how kids function at the first stage of these trials, it would be hard--", "start": 105.001, "stop": 121.362, "duration": 16.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "That has to do with your general rule, which -- which we shouldn't impose it at all.", "start": 121.362, "stop": 126.014, "duration": 4.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That -- that's right.", "start": 126.014, "stop": 126.797, "duration": 0.78}, {"text": "But--", "start": 126.797, "stop": 127.266, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "But if we go even to your second step rule--", "start": 127.266, "stop": 129.932, "duration": 2.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think--", "start": 129.932, "stop": 130.651, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--assuming we bifurcate--", "start": 130.651, "stop": 131.601, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, I hear--", "start": 131.601, "stop": 132.418, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--then -- then we still have the question of when do we permit a mandatory imposition?", "start": 132.418, "stop": 138.988, "duration": 6.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think there is no question, Justice Sotomayor, there would be more justification for those crimes where there is an intent to kill, because this Court in its jurisprudence had recognized that kind of hierarchy which you've outlined and is exhibited in Enmund and then in the Court's other cases.", "start": 138.988, "stop": 156.034, "duration": 17.05}, {"text": "Now, it's true that in -- in Arkansas under this provision an adult would still be subject to the death penalty, because they used this \"recklessness\" language so that even a focus on \"intent to kill\" that we addressed in Enmund might not categorically protect these other juveniles, which I think the Court can rightly acknowledge have diminished culpability.", "start": 156.034, "stop": 177.363, "duration": 21.33}, {"text": "It's also worth noting that in many of these States where there are children being sentenced to life without parole, there is no confusion about this.", "start": 177.363, "stop": 185.203, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "They are being convicted of homicide offenses for which there is no intent to kill.", "start": 185.203, "stop": 188.505, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "No dispute.", "start": 188.505, "stop": 189.138, "duration": 0.63}, {"text": "Those jurisdictions, those provisions would likely be addressed by the Enmund analysis.", "start": 189.138, "stop": 196.361, "duration": 7.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in fact, Jackson was convicted with a nonintent, just a felony--", "start": 196.361, "stop": 202.764, "duration": 6.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it would -- you're absolutely right that it's felony murder, but it's a little different.", "start": 202.764, "stop": 207.134, "duration": 4.37}, {"text": "In Arkansas, if you cooperate or give aid to someone who commits a crime, even if it's not intentional, if it's a reckless indifference to life, you can be found guilty of what is capital felony murder.", "start": 207.134, "stop": 222.061, "duration": 14.93}, {"text": "And the Arkansas court has interpreted that to mean for an adult you'd be subject to the death penalty.", "start": 222.061, "stop": 227.632, "duration": 5.57}, {"text": "And here Kuntrell Jackson was subject to life without parole.", "start": 227.632, "stop": 230.298, "duration": 2.67}, {"text": "The State argues that there was support for that and even some kind of intent, because there was a dispute about the words -- just quickly, you know, these three--", "start": 230.298, "stop": 239.44, "duration": 9.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It doesn't matter.", "start": 239.44, "stop": 240.123, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 240.123, "stop": 240.64, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "The jury didn't have to -- all the jury found was that he didn't meet his affirmative burden of proving.", "start": 240.64, "stop": 246.609, "duration": 5.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 246.609, "stop": 247.226, "duration": 0.62}, {"text": "That's exactly right.", "start": 247.226, "stop": 247.793, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "And he didn't counsel -- they didn't make a finding--", "start": 247.793, "stop": 249.811, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's exactly right.", "start": 249.811, "stop": 250.378, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--as to what words were used and what the intent was.", "start": 250.378, "stop": 252.863, "duration": 2.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that's exactly right.", "start": 252.863, "stop": 253.847, "duration": 0.98}, {"text": "And the dissenters of the Arkansas Supreme Court relied on that in making the determination that they did not conclude that intent had been established here in a way that would support the judgment that -- that we seek.", "start": 253.847, "stop": 264.238, "duration": 10.39}, {"text": "But that goes back to one of the earlier questions that was posed about what happens at the guilt phase.", "start": 264.238, "stop": 269.292, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "Is it -- Justice Kennedy, it is true that in Alabama and in most jurisdictions, you would not be permitted to tell the jury what the sentencing outcome would be.", "start": 269.292, "stop": 277.396, "duration": 8.1}, {"text": "And in many of these cases there -- there isn't a lesser included.", "start": 277.396, "stop": 280.85, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "That's going to be up to the -- to the prosecution in -- in some of these crimes.", "start": 280.85, "stop": 284.818, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "And there are a range of offenses for which that would not help a jury kind of deal with the -- the kind of -- the choice that--", "start": 284.818, "stop": 291.472, "duration": 6.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that what -- is that true under the law of Arkansas?", "start": 291.472, "stop": 293.84, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "In most jurisdictions, I would think if -- if someone's charged with the highest degree of homicide, the defense can request an instruction on -- you don't have to have a separate charge on a lesser included offense; the defense can request an instruction on lesser included offenses if it could be supported by the evidence.", "start": 293.84, "stop": 314.088, "duration": 20.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It -- it would really depend, Justice Alito, on the facts.", "start": 314.088, "stop": 317.29, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "For example, one of our provisions in Alabama makes the -- the crime sort of a -- a homicide a capital crime if the victim is under the age of 14.", "start": 317.29, "stop": 325.545, "duration": 8.25}, {"text": "You're not entitled to some diminished culpability, some other kind of homicide charge unless there's something else going on that would support that.", "start": 325.545, "stop": 333.901, "duration": 8.36}, {"text": "Our laws and this Court's law say there has to be evidence in support of that lesser included instruction before the court is constitutionally obligated to provide it.", "start": 333.901, "stop": 341.421, "duration": 7.52}, {"text": "And so, for that reason, it's not a given that that would happen.", "start": 341.421, "stop": 345.373, "duration": 3.95}, {"text": "And I think the challenge with the mandatory scheme that we've been talking about in both of these cases is that it does put the sentencer in a very difficult situation, where there is no ability to consider the age; there is no ability to consider the factual diminished culpability that might exist in one case or the other; no ability in either of these cases to consider the fact that an older codefendant got a lesser sentence.", "start": 345.373, "stop": 368.322, "duration": 22.95}, {"text": "That there is something else going on here that -- that goes beyond just the particulars of this crime and this particular offender's culpability.", "start": 368.322, "stop": 375.911, "duration": 7.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Before we leave it, could -- could -- what was the instruction the jury was given?", "start": 375.911, "stop": 380.03, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "Was it you find him guilty if he was deliberately indifferent, if he was recklessly -- what are the words they used?", "start": 380.03, "stop": 386.184, "duration": 6.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's a reckless indifference to life.", "start": 386.184, "stop": 388.486, "duration": 2.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "If he was recklessly indifferent to life.", "start": 388.486, "stop": 391.338, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if he gave aid or assistance to someone in that capacity, and the question, Justice Breyer, turned on -- on this statement made that the -- the codefendant who testified against Kuntrell Jackson--", "start": 391.338, "stop": 403.079, "duration": 11.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 403.079, "stop": 403.529, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--initially told the police he -- that he came in and said we ain't playing, and then he testified that he said,", "start": 403.529, "stop": 408.299, "duration": 4.77}, {"text": "\"I thought y'all were -- were playing. \"", "start": 408.299, "stop": 410.399, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not sure reckless indifference means that.", "start": 410.399, "stop": 413.101, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "Meaning if he knew they were carrying guns, doesn't that make him liable for the reckless indifference--", "start": 413.101, "stop": 420.607, "duration": 7.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well--", "start": 420.607, "stop": 421.04, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--whether he thought they would use them or not?", "start": 421.04, "stop": 422.709, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, and that's what the State argued here, is that the fact that he had knowledge of this gun and that they went in there made him guilty of reckless indifference even though it didn't create the kind of intent to kill that -- that we typically require for these kinds of showings.", "start": 422.709, "stop": 437.385, "duration": 14.68}, {"text": "That's again why there was the significance around this language, that if you come in and you say something declaratory that suggests that it's directed at the victim, it might help kind of support that intent finding if you don't--", "start": 437.385, "stop": 447.524, "duration": 10.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Reckless -- reckless indifference to life suffices for the death penalty for an adult.", "start": 447.524, "stop": 455.696, "duration": 8.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 455.696, "stop": 456.763, "duration": 1.07}, {"text": "What -- what the Court does--", "start": 456.763, "stop": 457.763, "duration": 1}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "If that's right, then we'd -- you would have to argue on, if we took this tack--", "start": 457.763, "stop": 462.617, "duration": 4.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That--", "start": 462.617, "stop": 463.217, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--which I don't know that we would--", "start": 463.217, "stop": 464.202, "duration": 0.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's--", "start": 464.202, "stop": 464.636, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--but that you cannot sentence a juvenile to life without parole for murder unless he, e.g., specifically intends the death or something equivalent, but something stronger than reckless indifference to life.", "start": 464.636, "stop": 481.346, "duration": 16.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That -- that's correct, Justice Breyer.", "start": 481.346, "stop": 483.031, "duration": 1.69}, {"text": "And, again, I think that this Court knows its own precedents, but as you'll recall, Tison followed Enmund, and in Tison v. Arizona is when the Court allowed there to be this kind of room around this intent standard in the way that you just described.", "start": 483.031, "stop": 496.34, "duration": 13.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, you would draw the line at -- at a specific intent to kill?", "start": 496.34, "stop": 499.892, "duration": 3.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Again, my -- I would -- I would categorically prohibit no matter what the intent is.", "start": 499.892, "stop": 505.629, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "I think particularly for children at this age.", "start": 505.629, "stop": 507.629, "duration": 2}, {"text": "What I think this case highlights, what's meant by", "start": 507.629, "stop": 511.45, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "\"I thought you all were playing. \"", "start": 511.45, "stop": 512.433, "duration": 0.98}, {"text": "versus \"we ain't playing\" isn't a very good indicator of whether someone should be subject to life without parole.", "start": 512.433, "stop": 518.021, "duration": 5.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if it was a lot clearer?", "start": 518.021, "stop": 519.054, "duration": 1.03}, {"text": "What if they had said, okay, before we go in, let's understand what's going on here; Shields has got -- has got the sawed-off shotgun, and if we need to use it, we'll use it; we'll do whatever it takes to -- to bring this off?", "start": 519.054, "stop": 531.611, "duration": 12.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I think the evidence--", "start": 531.611, "stop": 533.146, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "There might not be a specific intent--", "start": 533.146, "stop": 534.632, "duration": 1.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 534.632, "stop": 535.265, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--to kill there.", "start": 535.265, "stop": 535.798, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 535.798, "stop": 536.365, "duration": 0.57}, {"text": "I think the evidence that would support a finding of aggravated murder would obviously be stronger, but even there -- and this is what the Court points out in -- in Roper, the -- the decisionmaking of children, that the thinking of children is categorically different.", "start": 536.365, "stop": 549.992, "duration": 13.63}, {"text": "They're not thinking three steps ahead; they're not thinking about consequences; they're not actually experienced enough with the world to understand how they deal with their frustrations in the same way that an adult is.", "start": 549.992, "stop": 561.783, "duration": 11.79}, {"text": "And so, their judgments about what they intend to do, their declarations, mean something very, very different.", "start": 561.783, "stop": 567.52, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "And one of the factors that we haven't talked about, but I just want to emphasize, is it's not just their inherent internal attributes; it's also the external circumstances that they find themselves in.", "start": 567.52, "stop": 577.392, "duration": 9.87}, {"text": "Kuntrell Jackson was born in a household where there was nothing but violence and guns and people shooting each other.", "start": 577.392, "stop": 583.713, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "His grandmother shot his uncle.", "start": 583.713, "stop": 585.665, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "His mother shot a neighbor.", "start": 585.665, "stop": 586.881, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "His brother shot someone.", "start": 586.881, "stop": 588.367, "duration": 1.49}, {"text": "They were all put to jail.", "start": 588.367, "stop": 589.7, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "But, unlike an adult, these children don't have the ability to escape.", "start": 589.7, "stop": 593.671, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "A child of 14 cannot leave his criminogenic or violent environment.", "start": 593.671, "stop": 598.489, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "They have no control over that.", "start": 598.489, "stop": 599.841, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "And--", "start": 599.841, "stop": 600.375, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. -- I'm sorry; go ahead.", "start": 600.375, "stop": 601.691, "duration": 1.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And just because of that, I think it does reinforce why even their judgments, their so-called intentional judgments, reflect a very different kind of understanding of their character, their potential for rehabilitation, than it would with an adult.", "start": 601.691, "stop": 614.334, "duration": 12.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "One of the arguments that the State makes is that when you look at all these numbers, the number that is most different between this pair of cases and Graham is the denominator.", "start": 614.334, "stop": 626.392, "duration": 12.06}, {"text": "And I am wondering whether you would address that.", "start": 626.392, "stop": 628.475, "duration": 2.08}, {"text": "What kind of denominator we should be using here and how it compares to the denominators that we have used in past cases.", "start": 628.475, "stop": 634.998, "duration": 6.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 634.998, "stop": 635.698, "duration": 0.7}, {"text": "I think, first of all, it is true that homicide offenses are less common than non-homicidic offenses.", "start": 635.698, "stop": 641.952, "duration": 6.25}, {"text": "In Graham, this Court looked at a range of non-homicide crimes, and that was a huge number, 300,000, that's largely because we were talking about a multitude of offenses and here we are talking about a single offense.", "start": 641.952, "stop": 655.359, "duration": 13.41}, {"text": "I think the fact that there have been 7,000 children arrested for homicide and non-negligent murder -- manslaughter, over this 40-year time period and only 79 children have been sentenced to life without parole is a significant fact that reinforces our claim that this is a very rare sentence.", "start": 655.359, "stop": 674.256, "duration": 18.9}, {"text": "That is 1 percent.", "start": 674.256, "stop": 675.423, "duration": 1.17}, {"text": "And the fact that it's over 40 years, that's also true for the 79.", "start": 675.423, "stop": 679.641, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "We got to that--", "start": 679.641, "stop": 680.158, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's arrests to start out with, it's not -- it's not convictions.", "start": 680.158, "stop": 684.612, "duration": 4.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right.", "start": 684.612, "stop": 685.279, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And it's not for the type of offense for which one could be sentenced to life imprisonment without parole, it's a broader category of homicide offenses.", "start": 685.279, "stop": 695.651, "duration": 10.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you're absolutely right, Justice Alito, on the first point, that these are arrest data.", "start": 695.651, "stop": 699.721, "duration": 4.07}, {"text": "Of course, that's what we used in Graham, because again in this cohort, conviction data is simply very difficult to get.", "start": 699.721, "stop": 705.608, "duration": 5.89}, {"text": "But it's not true that only children arrested for aggravated murder are subject to life without parole.", "start": 705.608, "stop": 712.879, "duration": 7.27}, {"text": "As I have mentioned, in the States that create the largest population of these kids, all kinds of homicide can subject you to life without parole.", "start": 712.879, "stop": 721.635, "duration": 8.76}, {"text": "So it is true--", "start": 721.635, "stop": 722.368, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it true that in the States that permit life without parole for a minor homicide -- a minor murder, a person -- a minor convicted of -- of murder, that that is permitted for every non-negligent homicide?", "start": 722.368, "stop": 740.365, "duration": 18}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--In some States, yes.", "start": 740.365, "stop": 743.198, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "That is to the extent that you get convicted of murder some of these States, South Dakota and Pennsylvania come to mind, whether it's first degree or second degree, you are subject to life imprisonment without parole and it is a mandatory sentence.", "start": 743.198, "stop": 754.956, "duration": 11.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Some States, but not in all--", "start": 754.956, "stop": 756.391, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not in all States, that's true.", "start": 756.391, "stop": 757.725, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--So you have a very imprecise denominator, you have arrests for a broader category of offenses.", "start": 757.725, "stop": 763.312, "duration": 5.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 763.312, "stop": 763.862, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "But I don't think--", "start": 763.862, "stop": 764.864, "duration": 1}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don't know how much smaller that number would be if we narrowed it down appropriately, do we?", "start": 764.864, "stop": 770.051, "duration": 5.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, we can't get beyond what the data tell us.", "start": 770.051, "stop": 774.02, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "But I want to suggest it's no less precise than what this Court had to deal with in Graham.", "start": 774.02, "stop": 777.989, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "In Graham, we talked about 380,000 non-homicide offenders.", "start": 777.989, "stop": 782.208, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "Half of that class were people convicted of drug crimes, which no one has suggested would subject you to life without parole.", "start": 782.208, "stop": 789.362, "duration": 7.15}, {"text": "Another 60,000 were convicted of assaults and kids get into fights all the time.", "start": 789.362, "stop": 794.433, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "But we used the aggregate of all of those numbers when we made that comparison.", "start": 794.433, "stop": 798.735, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "So I'd actually argue that we are dealing here with a category definition that is much more precise than what we dealt with in Graham.", "start": 798.735, "stop": 806.824, "duration": 8.09}, {"text": "And, Justice Kagan, to return to your question we do have some precedence that help us with this.", "start": 806.824, "stop": 810.793, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "In Coker v. Georgia, this Court was trying to make an assessment about the propriety of the death penalty for the crime of rape.", "start": 810.793, "stop": 818.132, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "And what the Court noted was that nine out of ten of the jury that made decisions about life versus death chose life.", "start": 818.132, "stop": 826.887, "duration": 8.75}, {"text": "And there we were talking about a death rate, if you will, of 10 percent.", "start": 826.887, "stop": 833.825, "duration": 6.94}, {"text": "Here, with a larger universe, we are talking about a rate of 1 percent.", "start": 833.825, "stop": 835.927, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you -- think about this, which is not your favorite position, but it's a position you've taken.", "start": 835.927, "stop": 844.949, "duration": 9.02}, {"text": "It's the same question I asked before.", "start": 844.949, "stop": 847.818, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "If I say, well, doesn't there have to be some line, 3 years old, you will say of course.", "start": 847.818, "stop": 854.722, "duration": 6.9}, {"text": "10 years old, you will say of course.", "start": 854.722, "stop": 857.524, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "But nobody -- there is no problem with sentencing 10-year-olds to life without parole.", "start": 857.524, "stop": 862.175, "duration": 4.65}, {"text": "12 years old.", "start": 862.175, "stop": 863.76, "duration": 1.59}, {"text": "Well, hum, now maybe your opponents want to defend that.", "start": 863.76, "stop": 869.247, "duration": 5.49}, {"text": "13 years old, 14 years old and of course I am walking right into the buzz saw, well, leave it up to the legislature.", "start": 869.247, "stop": 876.918, "duration": 7.67}, {"text": "But suppose that there's something to be said for not leaving it up to the legislature, at least for the numbers that were in that range.", "start": 876.918, "stop": 886.041, "duration": 9.12}, {"text": "But how would you defend the cutoff for no life without parole at say 14, older than 14, rather than older than 15, rather than older than 13.", "start": 886.041, "stop": 898.934, "duration": 12.89}, {"text": "What kind of argument is there that isn't totally random for picking that number as the age below which you cannot impose life without parole even for the most horrendous murder.", "start": 898.934, "stop": 911.074, "duration": 12.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yeah.", "start": 911.074, "stop": 911.508, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "I think two nonrandom arguments can be made for the two ages.", "start": 911.508, "stop": 916.645, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "I will start with the young age of 14.", "start": 916.645, "stop": 918.664, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "When you consider the fact that 13 jurisdictions have thought about this, and have all but one set the age above 14, I think we can then rely on that to make a determination that if there is a minimum age, it's above 14.", "start": 918.664, "stop": 932.588, "duration": 13.92}, {"text": "I think we can also, consistent with this Court's precedents, look at the frequency of the sentence for this population.", "start": 932.588, "stop": 939.494, "duration": 6.91}, {"text": "Most States have never sentenced a child to life without parole for a crime at 14.", "start": 939.494, "stop": 944.479, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "They've just never done it.", "start": 944.479, "stop": 945.581, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "32 States, there are no children 14 and younger serving life without parole.", "start": 945.581, "stop": 949.883, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "And so, I think that allows this Court in a very nonrandom way to defend that judgment.", "start": 949.883, "stop": 955.437, "duration": 5.55}, {"text": "But I also think a nonrandom argument can be made to draw the line at 18.", "start": 955.437, "stop": 960.424, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "That is offenders under the age of 18.", "start": 960.424, "stop": 962.943, "duration": 2.52}, {"text": "That's exactly what this Court has done in Roper, it's what this Court has done in Graham.", "start": 962.943, "stop": 967.078, "duration": 4.13}, {"text": "What we have relied on about juvenile status is applicable to that poll.", "start": 967.078, "stop": 971.213, "duration": 4.13}, {"text": "I concede that these other indicia are not quite as compelling.", "start": 971.213, "stop": 976.034, "duration": 4.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "18, you use for a lot of purposes, 18 -- you could say, okay, 18.", "start": 976.034, "stop": 981.587, "duration": 5.55}, {"text": "The difficulty with 18 is you are running into 2300, not 79.", "start": 981.587, "stop": 987.324, "duration": 5.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right--", "start": 987.324, "stop": 988.008, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the difficulty is that in Roper, it said, well, don't worry so much about not having the death penalty, the other one, don't worry so much about it because there's always life without parole.", "start": 988.008, "stop": 998.549, "duration": 10.54}, {"text": "And the fact that 18-year-olds or 17-year-olds in many respects are quite mature or at least can be.", "start": 998.549, "stop": 1004.703, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "And so that makes 18 seem not quite right.", "start": 1004.703, "stop": 1009.338, "duration": 4.63}, {"text": "But there's a problem with each of them, so that's--", "start": 1009.338, "stop": 1012.207, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yeah, but I guess just on that point, Justice Breyer, I think you're right that the indicia are more complicated.", "start": 1012.207, "stop": 1019.613, "duration": 7.41}, {"text": "But I want to just stress that they are less meaningful here.", "start": 1019.613, "stop": 1022.414, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "Because with mandatory sentences, they don't tell you the same thing they do in these other contexts.", "start": 1022.414, "stop": 1027.383, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "But I also think it's true that we have recognized that up until the age of 18, you are a juvenile, your status is coherent with what the Court has recognized in these other cases.", "start": 1027.383, "stop": 1038.191, "duration": 10.81}, {"text": "And so I do think it's defensible there.", "start": 1038.191, "stop": 1040.193, "duration": 2}, {"text": "While it's true that you are more developed than a child of 14 or a child of 10, it's also true that you are not an adult.", "start": 1040.193, "stop": 1047.547, "duration": 7.35}, {"text": "And we make that distinction in lots of ways.", "start": 1047.547, "stop": 1049.815, "duration": 2.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Any other distinction that you have been able to think of growing out of the literature or growing out of the law where the cutoff for some roughly comparable series of things is between 14 and 15 or between 14 and 16, or something like that.", "start": 1049.815, "stop": 1067.443, "duration": 17.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, yes, this Court in Thompson made a distinction between offenders that were under the age of 15, 15 and younger, then older offenders.", "start": 1067.443, "stop": 1073.947, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "And for 20 some years, the law in this country was you could not subject younger offenders to the death penalty in ways that you could older offenders.", "start": 1073.947, "stop": 1081.436, "duration": 7.49}, {"text": "And so there is clearly precedent for that and we have appended also lots of statutes, I mean, that also make those kinds of distinctions.", "start": 1081.436, "stop": 1088.607, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "I mean, we do draw these lines frequently in a range of areas, not just dealing with the constitutional questions that we are dealing with here.", "start": 1088.607, "stop": 1096.046, "duration": 7.44}, {"text": "But just kind of to complete my analysis, Justice Kagan, about these comparisons.", "start": 1096.046, "stop": 1100.015, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "The other point that I will reference is that in Thompson, this Court was also struggling over this question about frequency and rarity.", "start": 1100.015, "stop": 1107.837, "duration": 7.82}, {"text": "And what the Court did there was actually look at the number of juveniles that were sentenced to death under the age of 16 that were on death row and compared them to the number of people on death row at the time, and they noted that it was.36 percent of the population of people on death row.", "start": 1107.837, "stop": 1126.049, "duration": 18.21}, {"text": "If you did the same thing here, the Sentencing Project reports that there are over 41,000 people in the United States serving sentences of life imprisonment without parole.", "start": 1126.049, "stop": 1134.653, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "And if you compare our number of 79 to that, that is actually again a lower proportion of people serving life without parole than the Court found to be constitutionally significant in Thompson.", "start": 1134.653, "stop": 1145.361, "duration": 10.71}, {"text": "So I think Thompson and Coker all reinforce what we are saying here, that this is an exceedingly rare sentence where the majority of States have never chose to impose it.", "start": 1145.361, "stop": 1155.416, "duration": 10.05}, {"text": "That would provide a basis for this Court to conclude that it is cruel and unusual.", "start": 1155.416, "stop": 1160.203, "duration": 4.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "You are making an argument now in Jackson's case.", "start": 1160.203, "stop": 1165.271, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "Jackson was the felony murder case and I think at least in your brief, you made the argument it was just happenstance and bad luck that in Jackson's case the shop attendant was killed.", "start": 1165.271, "stop": 1186.519, "duration": 21.25}, {"text": "And in Graham's case, the person who was assaulted survived.", "start": 1186.519, "stop": 1193.674, "duration": 7.15}, {"text": "But your argument to us seems to make no distinction between the two cases.", "start": 1193.674, "stop": 1200.361, "duration": 6.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, no, I -- I -- I don't intend to do that Justice Ginsburg.", "start": 1200.361, "stop": 1203.73, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "I think -- I think there is a distinction, there is no question that there is a stronger argument that by traditional measures there is lower culpability in Kuntrell Jackson's case.", "start": 1203.73, "stop": 1212.502, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "He was not found to have specifically intended to kill.", "start": 1212.502, "stop": 1215.704, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "In the State of Alabama he could not have been subject to life without parole, and there are States where he would not be subject to that, based on his degree of culpability.", "start": 1215.704, "stop": 1225.412, "duration": 9.71}, {"text": "I -- I guess my -- my -- my point is that even there, there is a challenge that if the Court wants to engage in that kind of thinking, what children intend because they are children is a very complicated question.", "start": 1225.412, "stop": 1240.338, "duration": 14.93}, {"text": "It's a very different question.", "start": 1240.338, "stop": 1241.155, "duration": 0.82}, {"text": "I don't mean to concede that it's an irrelevant question.", "start": 1241.155, "stop": 1244.457, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "I think the Court absolutely can and should conclude that there is diminished culpability in the Jackson case, and that is evident based on the facts in the crime.", "start": 1244.457, "stop": 1253.229, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "Actually it was the dissenter in -- in the Jackson case that made this observation about the consequences of crime.", "start": 1253.229, "stop": 1259.633, "duration": 6.4}, {"text": "And, of course, for many non-homicide crimes there are these kind of fortuities that sometimes prevent death wonderfully, and we were grateful for that.", "start": 1259.633, "stop": 1268.339, "duration": 8.71}, {"text": "My problem is that the differences between children and adults, these internal attributes, if you will, these deficits in judgment are not crime specific.", "start": 1268.339, "stop": 1278.377, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "The person who intends to kill doesn't actually have any better judgment, any more character, any more maturity, any more impulse control than the person who doesn't.", "start": 1278.377, "stop": 1289.835, "duration": 11.46}, {"text": "And a way of characterizing a rule would be to recognize that and to create a categorical ban.", "start": 1289.835, "stop": 1296.839, "duration": 7}, {"text": "If there are no further questions, I will reserve the rest of my time for rebuttal.", "start": 1296.839, "stop": 1302.493, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 1302.493, "stop": 1304.345, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "Mr. Holt?", "start": 1304.345, "stop": 1311.016, "duration": 6.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 1311.016, "stop": 1314.467, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "The decision below falls squarely within the framework of Roper and Graham, and there are three reasons to affirm this judgment.", "start": 1314.467, "stop": 1321.789, "duration": 7.32}, {"text": "First, murder is the worst of all crimes.", "start": 1321.789, "stop": 1324.758, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "Society has drawn that line.", "start": 1324.758, "stop": 1327.027, "duration": 2.27}, {"text": "Second, legislatures have the power to authorize sentences that are commensurate with crimes like murder.", "start": 1327.027, "stop": 1334.631, "duration": 7.6}, {"text": "Third, Jackson has not demonstrated any consensus in this case against the practice, and in fact, there is a supermajority of States and of governments that authorize this sentence.", "start": 1334.631, "stop": 1347.105, "duration": 12.47}, {"text": "The landscape of this case is -- is different than Graham, because in Graham no one was -- no one was killed.", "start": 1347.105, "stop": 1355.292, "duration": 8.19}, {"text": "Terrence Graham was lucky no one was killed, because he acted with a reckless disregard for human life as well, but it's an important thing in our law that the law punishes the -- the result, the harm that is inflicted.", "start": 1355.292, "stop": 1368.968, "duration": 13.68}, {"text": "And if I could, go to the Arkansas statute.", "start": 1368.968, "stop": 1373.003, "duration": 4.03}, {"text": "Jackson was charged with the highest crime you could be charged with in Arkansas, it was capital felony murder.", "start": 1373.003, "stop": 1381.442, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "In that the legislature has set out several enumerated, several violent felonies that if you commit this particular crime -- and aggravated robbery is one of them -- if you commit that crime and in the course and furtherance of that, you or an accomplice act with extreme indifference to the value of human life during the commission of it or in the flight from it, then you are guilty of capital felony murder.", "start": 1381.442, "stop": 1408.343, "duration": 26.9}, {"text": "So, in this case the jury was called upon, because there were other accomplices with Kuntrell Jackson, they were called on to determine whether or not Kuntrell Jackson acted as an accomplice, whether he aided and assisted and whether or not he or an accomplice acted with extreme indifference to the value of human life.", "start": 1408.343, "stop": 1433.127, "duration": 24.78}, {"text": "In that process, Kuntrell Jackson asserted the affirmative defense that essentially is available for capital murder.", "start": 1433.127, "stop": 1444.099, "duration": 10.97}, {"text": "He said that, I did not have -- I was not the triggerman, and I did not -- I did not commit the homicide offense, and I did not aid or procure counsel, all of those are listed -- the exact words of the affirmative defense are listed in our brief at page 4.", "start": 1444.099, "stop": 1462.496, "duration": 18.4}, {"text": "And -- but he asserted that defense.", "start": 1462.496, "stop": 1466.115, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "The Arkansas Supreme Court noted in its opinion that in his challenge to the sufficiency of the evidence, that there was sufficient evidence to convict him of capital murder and that the jury was well within its right to believe that he said that he -- that when he walked in and took -- took the lead in this robbery that he said, \"We ain't playing\", and after that the clerk responded that she was going to call the police--", "start": 1466.115, "stop": 1493.265, "duration": 27.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Counsel, I -- I -- I know that this seems like block building, but I -- I think of law as sort of logical.", "start": 1493.265, "stop": 1501.621, "duration": 8.36}, {"text": "If you are involved in a felony, and you counsel the felony where someone dies under Arkansas law, you are guilty of felony murder, correct?", "start": 1501.621, "stop": 1511.994, "duration": 10.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Of capital felony murder, yes, Your Honor.", "start": 1511.994, "stop": 1513.846, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So whether or not that he intended to counsel the crime, he was guilty of felony murder, unless he could prove the affirmative defense, right?", "start": 1513.846, "stop": 1524.303, "duration": 10.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 1524.303, "stop": 1524.903, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So obviously he didn't prove the affirmative defense, but that doesn't mean that the jury actually found that he used one set of words or another.", "start": 1524.903, "stop": 1537.477, "duration": 12.57}, {"text": "It just means that they didn't believe that he had proven by his burden of proof that he had not counseled, correct?", "start": 1537.477, "stop": 1547.516, "duration": 10.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 1547.516, "stop": 1548.934, "duration": 1.42}, {"text": "The Arkansas Supreme Court said they could -- they could accept that as -- they pointed to that as--", "start": 1548.934, "stop": 1554.02, "duration": 5.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "As a possibility--", "start": 1554.02, "stop": 1554.938, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--As a possibility, yes.", "start": 1554.938, "stop": 1555.888, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But not that it was an actual finding by the jury?", "start": 1555.888, "stop": 1558.207, "duration": 2.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 1558.207, "stop": 1558.64, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 1558.64, "stop": 1559.157, "duration": 0.52}, {"text": "It was not an actual finding--", "start": 1559.157, "stop": 1560.326, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 1560.326, "stop": 1561.059, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--because an actual -- in regard to sentences in terms of years, we don't require that individualized responsibility that we do, for instance, in a death penalty case.", "start": 1561.059, "stop": 1570.882, "duration": 9.82}, {"text": "So--", "start": 1570.882, "stop": 1571.732, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, so in Arkansas if a 13-year-old or a 14-year-old is in a get-away car and knowingly accepts the money that someone gets from a robbery and intends to drive off with it, and that other person shoots the teller and kills him, then that individual who is 14 years old is guilty of felony murder, capital felony murder?", "start": 1571.732, "stop": 1602.351, "duration": 30.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Your Honor--", "start": 1602.351, "stop": 1603.401, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "He aided?", "start": 1603.401, "stop": 1604.536, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "Is that right or not?", "start": 1604.536, "stop": 1607.486, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 1607.486, "stop": 1609.938, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 1609.938, "stop": 1610.44, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "If that's right, do -- do you think that such a person is less culpable, knowing only that, than a person who actually takes out a gun and shoots the teller?", "start": 1610.44, "stop": 1621.162, "duration": 10.72}, {"text": "Morally speaking?", "start": 1621.162, "stop": 1623.698, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 1623.698, "stop": 1624.531, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "Yes.", "start": 1624.531, "stop": 1625.2, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 1625.2, "stop": 1625.816, "duration": 0.62}, {"text": "Now, if the answer to that question is yes, what is the argument for not being able to tell that to the jury or judge who is going to impose the sentence?", "start": 1625.816, "stop": 1636.005, "duration": 10.19}, {"text": "What is the argument for not allowing a judge or a jury, at least to think about that question, before they have -- before imposing mandatory life without parole?", "start": 1636.005, "stop": 1649.415, "duration": 13.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor, that -- that -- telling a jury about that doesn't go to their guilt.", "start": 1649.415, "stop": 1654.3, "duration": 4.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I know.", "start": 1654.3, "stop": 1655.135, "duration": 0.84}, {"text": "I mean my obvious point is that -- that the Arkansas system, once we have he was the get-away driver or assisted the get-away driver, they must sentence him at that age, or despite that age, to life without parole.", "start": 1655.135, "stop": 1672.43, "duration": 17.3}, {"text": "And so, the other side is saying, well, at the very least -- he has three other positions -- but at the very least, the Constitution, maybe it's the due process clause, requires the sentencer to take that into account, the fact that he was just the assistant get-away driver and may not have thought about the murder in reality, and may not have expected it in reality.", "start": 1672.43, "stop": 1698.412, "duration": 25.98}, {"text": "Why not have to take that into account in sentencing?", "start": 1698.412, "stop": 1701.798, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "That's the argument.", "start": 1701.798, "stop": 1702.55, "duration": 0.75}, {"text": "I want to hear directly your answer to that, which is taking the fourth or possibly the least weakest of his positions or the least radical.", "start": 1702.55, "stop": 1709.554, "duration": 7}, {"text": "What's your answer to that?", "start": 1709.554, "stop": 1710.906, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, it's -- a legislative judgment has been made with regard to drawing a baseline for all murderers, whether they are juvenile murderers, whether they are get-away drivers.", "start": 1710.906, "stop": 1723.196, "duration": 12.29}, {"text": "And when you -- when you counsel or aid or do anything that gets you liability for being a capital murderer, then that's the -- that is the minimum sentence.", "start": 1723.196, "stop": 1735.354, "duration": 12.16}, {"text": "What he has gotten, on account of his youth, is he's gotten -- this -- this Court decided in Roper in that he could not -- he could not get the death penalty.", "start": 1735.354, "stop": 1745.976, "duration": 10.62}, {"text": "All of those individualized characteristics that would give him the lesser penalty, he doesn't even have to put on.", "start": 1745.976, "stop": 1751.464, "duration": 5.49}, {"text": "It's swept off the table because he is not exposed.", "start": 1751.464, "stop": 1754.681, "duration": 3.22}, {"text": "And that is -- those are all those factors in terms of what he -- what he might -- that might mitigate.", "start": 1754.681, "stop": 1761.769, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "So he would actually would sort of be double dipping to come back again and say, oh, and by the way, I'm a youth, so I should even -- I should get not the lesser punishment, I should get the lesser, lesser punishment.", "start": 1761.769, "stop": 1773.477, "duration": 11.71}, {"text": "So there is a certain symmetry that this case has with the Graham case, in that the Graham case was very specific about the way it defined itself.", "start": 1773.477, "stop": 1786.037, "duration": 12.56}, {"text": "One commentator has made the note that the majority opinion in Graham contained the word non-homicide 47 times.", "start": 1786.037, "stop": 1794.575, "duration": 8.54}, {"text": "Graham essentially said what it wasn't.", "start": 1794.575, "stop": 1799.71, "duration": 5.13}, {"text": "It wasn't a homicide.", "start": 1799.71, "stop": 1801.562, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "It was that other line that society draws between homicide and every other crime.", "start": 1801.562, "stop": 1807.383, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "And crimes are -- the criminal statutes are scalar.", "start": 1807.383, "stop": 1811.102, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "There's a certain amount of culpability that's built into each one of those, whether it be capital murder or first-degree murder, or second-degree murder.", "start": 1811.102, "stop": 1821.376, "duration": 10.27}, {"text": "And it does go on what you know, the -- the knowledge that you have.", "start": 1821.376, "stop": 1827.797, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "Maturity is taken into consideration, or immaturity is taken into consideration in capital murder in that you can't get the worst -- if you've been shown to do these acts, you can't get the worst punishment.", "start": 1827.797, "stop": 1839.271, "duration": 11.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is the standard in Arkansas for moving a child from the juvenile system?", "start": 1839.271, "stop": 1846.941, "duration": 7.67}, {"text": "We heard, I think, in Alabama it was -- was age 13?", "start": 1846.941, "stop": 1853.514, "duration": 6.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1853.514, "stop": 1854.281, "duration": 0.77}, {"text": "Your Honor--", "start": 1854.281, "stop": 1854.931, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was age 12.", "start": 1854.931, "stop": 1855.897, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 1855.897, "stop": 1856.383, "duration": 0.49}, {"text": "Your Honor, Arkansas has sort of a three-tier system.", "start": 1856.383, "stop": 1860.518, "duration": 4.13}, {"text": "The age for moving into the adult system is 14.", "start": 1860.518, "stop": 1864.737, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "And -- but the middle-tier system in Arkansas is called extended juvenile jurisdiction.", "start": 1864.737, "stop": 1871.393, "duration": 6.66}, {"text": "And in that particular case -- in those cases, the prosecutor can move to take a younger age and put in -- and it's a blended sentence between the -- and a youth is just found delinquent of a crime and not -- and found guilty.", "start": 1871.393, "stop": 1891.221, "duration": 19.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "What -- what are the factors the judges and prosecutors use in making that determination?", "start": 1891.221, "stop": 1899.576, "duration": 8.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, at age 14 -- and it's the specific -- there are specific crimes that a prosecutor would move a case into an adult court.", "start": 1899.576, "stop": 1910.184, "duration": 10.61}, {"text": "It is the prosecutor's discretion weighing -- there are 10 different factors that include the severity of the offense, the -- and -- but they also take into consideration the maturity of the -- of the youth, the--", "start": 1910.184, "stop": 1925.644, "duration": 15.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "But -- but if you submit that as a justification for your scheme, why couldn't those same factors be applied to the judge -- by the sentencing judge after the conviction?", "start": 1925.644, "stop": 1938.618, "duration": 12.97}, {"text": "In other words, all of the -- all of the discretion is up front before the conviction.", "start": 1938.618, "stop": 1945.105, "duration": 6.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, there is discretion up front, and that is the only -- that is the only instance when a defendant can actually challenge a transfer, where a prosecutor decides to put it.", "start": 1945.105, "stop": 1956.844, "duration": 11.74}, {"text": "But there are also -- so, there is -- there's discretion at the front end.", "start": 1956.844, "stop": 1961.481, "duration": 4.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I guess my point is, if the concern is that -- that we have too indefinite standards, too few specifics to guide the judge in determining whether there should be a life sentence, the same criticism could apply to the determination if they didn't put him in the adult system at the outset.", "start": 1961.481, "stop": 1978.409, "duration": 16.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor, the -- it is -- admittedly, it is at the discretion of the prosecutor on those ages to move it into the--", "start": 1978.409, "stop": 1991.334, "duration": 12.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I assume discretion is guided by certain standards or it's no discretion at all.", "start": 1991.334, "stop": 1995.538, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "So, there are standards.", "start": 1995.538, "stop": 1996.871, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Your Honor, the -- the prosecutor -- that -- that decision to move it in there is challengeable.", "start": 1996.871, "stop": 2006.26, "duration": 9.39}, {"text": "It is reviewable by a court.", "start": 2006.26, "stop": 2007.928, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "He moves -- the juvenile moves it to transfer it to -- back to juvenile.", "start": 2007.928, "stop": 2012.763, "duration": 4.83}, {"text": "That is appealed.", "start": 2012.763, "stop": 2014.099, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "That was done in this case, and then the Arkansas Court of Appeals reviewed that decision and said that the court -- the court's decision was not erroneous.", "start": 2014.099, "stop": 2025.14, "duration": 11.04}, {"text": "So, that -- that is the discretion that one would exercise on the front end.", "start": 2025.14, "stop": 2030.711, "duration": 5.57}, {"text": "Again, on the latter end, this Court has said in Harmelin that the individualized sentencing is not required, and, in fact, the -- all of the -- all of the -- the mitigating circumstances that would -- that have been considered because it's -- he's -- the death penalty has been taken off the table.", "start": 2030.711, "stop": 2052.724, "duration": 22.01}, {"text": "That's a big -- that's a big deal, especially in a case like this one where Kuntrell Jackson -- we believe the evidence showed that he also acted with reckless indifference to the value of human life, based -- based on the evidence in this case.", "start": 2052.724, "stop": 2067.584, "duration": 14.86}, {"text": "That he would be -- by way of analogy, that he would be a Tison offender himself.", "start": 2067.584, "stop": 2072.971, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "But irrespective of that, the legislature in Arkansas -- it's -- the legislative judgment has been that the minimum sentence that a person can receive for committing a capital murder in Arkansas is life without parole.", "start": 2072.971, "stop": 2090.432, "duration": 17.46}, {"text": "I would like to clarify one point that I think -- earlier that was made.", "start": 2090.432, "stop": 2097.269, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "The two other individuals in this particular case were -- one was a cousin who testified against Mr. Jackson, and he was 15.", "start": 2097.269, "stop": 2108.91, "duration": 11.64}, {"text": "He had turned 15 the day before this robbery.", "start": 2108.91, "stop": 2111.612, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "And the second, the second individual, the triggerman, was -- he was also 14, and he received a sentence of life without parole as well.", "start": 2111.612, "stop": 2123.42, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "It's our position that -- as is Alabama's, that the main -- the principal justification in this case lies with the retributive principle that society needs to convey the message that people that Laurie -- that Laurie Troup's life, the victim in this case, was more important than the money in that cash register.", "start": 2123.42, "stop": 2149.385, "duration": 25.97}, {"text": "The harm here was irrevocable.", "start": 2149.385, "stop": 2152.004, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "And this kind -- the punishment for this -- it's qualitative -- death -- the death penalty is qualitatively different.", "start": 2152.004, "stop": 2160.443, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "But the punishment for -- for this crime reinforces the sanctity of human life and it expresses the State's moral outrage that something like this could happen.", "start": 2160.443, "stop": 2171.234, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "We think that the respect due life is -- is what this message conveys, and it conveys it more as a life-without-parole sentence than it does life without.", "start": 2171.234, "stop": 2182.358, "duration": 11.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "You say the sanctity of human life, but you're dealing with a 14-year-old being sentenced to life in prison, so he will die in prison without any hope.", "start": 2182.358, "stop": 2199.235, "duration": 16.88}, {"text": "I mean, essentially, you're making a 14-year-old throwaway person.", "start": 2199.235, "stop": 2206.224, "duration": 6.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, I'd respectfully disagree that he's a throwaway person.", "start": 2206.224, "stop": 2212.994, "duration": 6.77}, {"text": "The -- we want to -- we want him to come to an understanding of his own humanity.", "start": 2212.994, "stop": 2219.065, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "We want him to realize the enormity of his crime.", "start": 2219.065, "stop": 2222, "duration": 2.93}, {"text": "I can only speak for Arkansas, but in Arkansas, instances -- it's not in the record, but this particular petitioner, Jackson has made efforts to obtain his GED; he has taken anger management classes.", "start": 2222, "stop": 2239.462, "duration": 17.46}, {"text": "You can -- juvenile life without parole -- people serving this sentence are enrolled in vo-tech programs in prison.", "start": 2239.462, "stop": 2249.001, "duration": 9.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry.", "start": 2249.001, "stop": 2249.485, "duration": 0.48}, {"text": "What hope does he have?", "start": 2249.485, "stop": 2250.937, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Excuse me?", "start": 2250.937, "stop": 2251.953, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "What hope does he have?", "start": 2251.953, "stop": 2252.954, "duration": 1}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, he has -- the hope that he may have is that he -- is an application for commutation through the parole board.", "start": 2252.954, "stop": 2263.177, "duration": 10.22}, {"text": "Other than that, he will -- or perhaps retroactive legislation--", "start": 2263.177, "stop": 2269.414, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry--", "start": 2269.414, "stop": 2270.097, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--if the legislature comes to another view.", "start": 2270.097, "stop": 2271.33, "duration": 1.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I thought he was life without parole.", "start": 2271.33, "stop": 2272.366, "duration": 1.04}, {"text": "I thought he was sentenced to life without parole.", "start": 2272.366, "stop": 2275.918, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "How can the parole board--", "start": 2275.918, "stop": 2277.084, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, what I'm saying is the parole board is -- reviews applications for commutation in Arkansas.", "start": 2277.084, "stop": 2284.174, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "So, he -- this particular Petitioner has not--", "start": 2284.174, "stop": 2287.959, "duration": 3.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many commutations of life imprisonment sentences are ordered every year in Arkansas?", "start": 2287.959, "stop": 2294.729, "duration": 6.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Your Honor, I don't have figures on that -- on how many per year, but there is a case that -- that listed -- it's Rogers v. State.", "start": 2294.729, "stop": 2308.455, "duration": 13.73}, {"text": "It is a 1979 case that actually listed -- 30 clemency requests were granted in the last 5 years from that opinion.", "start": 2308.455, "stop": 2319.445, "duration": 10.99}, {"text": "They were life sentences.", "start": 2319.445, "stop": 2321.463, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "From life sentences?", "start": 2321.463, "stop": 2322.549, "duration": 1.09}, {"text": "From life without parole?", "start": 2322.549, "stop": 2324.982, "duration": 2.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, life without -- life and life without parole in Arkansas are the same type of sentence.", "start": 2324.982, "stop": 2332.504, "duration": 7.52}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do we know how old Laurie Troup was when she was shot?", "start": 2332.504, "stop": 2336.972, "duration": 4.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 2336.972, "stop": 2337.891, "duration": 0.92}, {"text": "Laurie Troup was 28 years old when she was shot.", "start": 2337.891, "stop": 2342.46, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "She was discovered by her mother and her 11-year old son.", "start": 2342.46, "stop": 2346.164, "duration": 3.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand the arguments, which are very good ones, for the importance of Arkansas emphasizing the importance of life and not killing people.", "start": 2346.164, "stop": 2356.203, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "But a person who is an adult who is faced with the death penalty, which is certainly a strong statement along your lines, is permitted by the Constitution nonetheless to make any mitigating argument he wants.", "start": 2356.203, "stop": 2372.731, "duration": 16.53}, {"text": "And Arkansas has to do that.", "start": 2372.731, "stop": 2374.531, "duration": 1.8}, {"text": "They have to let him make any mitigating argument he wants.", "start": 2374.531, "stop": 2378.635, "duration": 4.1}, {"text": "And so, the argument here is basically, well, the same is true when a 14-year-old, because of the lack of maturity, faces life without parole.", "start": 2378.635, "stop": 2391.709, "duration": 13.07}, {"text": "And that seems to be the hard issue in this case.", "start": 2391.709, "stop": 2395.178, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "Just as -- just as the death penalty is unique for anyone and therefore requires mitigating elements, isn't the life without parole special enough for an adolescent that you have to let him at least make any mitigating arguments he wants?", "start": 2395.178, "stop": 2413.739, "duration": 18.56}, {"text": "Now, Arkansas hasn't really expressed a view in its legislation on that question, or maybe it has and just rejected it.", "start": 2413.739, "stop": 2420.728, "duration": 6.99}, {"text": "But I don't know.", "start": 2420.728, "stop": 2422.062, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "That's -- if you want to say something about that, I'd be interested.", "start": 2422.062, "stop": 2425.03, "duration": 2.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's -- that's not a view that -- that I know that's been expressed.", "start": 2425.03, "stop": 2431.684, "duration": 6.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2431.684, "stop": 2433.036, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "But I mean, that's what their brief is filled with on the other side, basically.", "start": 2433.036, "stop": 2437.105, "duration": 4.07}, {"text": "And so is Roper.", "start": 2437.105, "stop": 2438.19, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 2438.19, "stop": 2439.424, "duration": 1.23}, {"text": "But this -- this is qualitatively different.", "start": 2439.424, "stop": 2443.661, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "And -- and that's been taken off the table.", "start": 2443.661, "stop": 2447.03, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "I think that all of -- all of those things that he would put to get the -- that he would -- that he would put forward to get the lesser sentence is -- initially is that he would just get a -- as I said, a lesser -- lesser sentence.", "start": 2447.03, "stop": 2459.103, "duration": 12.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that because Arkansas has no life with parole?", "start": 2459.103, "stop": 2464.241, "duration": 5.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, the only provision, and -- and this does go to show that Arkansas has -- has thought about this in ways -- has make -- taken deliberate steps.", "start": 2464.241, "stop": 2474.28, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "In its extended juvenile jurisdiction, there is the provision that -- that a -- for instance, a 14-year-old in this particular case, if -- if they had deemed that they would go in extended juvenile jurisdiction could receive a life penalty, except it is life with parole, yes.", "start": 2474.28, "stop": 2494.176, "duration": 19.9}, {"text": "So, that is -- that--", "start": 2494.176, "stop": 2496.026, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's not available to an adult.", "start": 2496.026, "stop": 2497.728, "duration": 1.7}, {"text": "That's only available to--", "start": 2497.728, "stop": 2498.695, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Kent G. Holt", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's not available to an adult.", "start": 2498.695, "stop": 2499.478, "duration": 0.78}, {"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 2499.478, "stop": 2500.047, "duration": 0.57}, {"text": "As I -- as I was saying, the -- there's a certain constitutional symmetry to this case and to Graham's case because -- because Graham committed a -- a non-homicide offense and he was a youth, and so he had twice-diminished punishment.", "start": 2500.047, "stop": 2526.498, "duration": 26.45}, {"text": "But he only received one diminishment in his -- in his punishment, because he had -- he was -- he had twice-diminished culpability.", "start": 2526.498, "stop": 2535.853, "duration": 9.36}, {"text": "In this particular case, Jackson does not have twice-diminished culpability.", "start": 2535.853, "stop": 2542.274, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "He has -- he is a youth.", "start": 2542.274, "stop": 2544.443, "duration": 2.17}, {"text": "Even if he were to -- even if we were to say that, well, he didn't pull the trigger, or we can't show that he didn't -- that he acted -- didn't act with reckless indifference -- even if we were to say that that was twice-diminished, he is still criminally responsible.", "start": 2544.443, "stop": 2559.719, "duration": 15.28}, {"text": "There's not a -- there's not a special class of not guilty by reason of youth.", "start": 2559.719, "stop": 2564.688, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "He is still criminally responsible for what he did.", "start": 2564.688, "stop": 2568.824, "duration": 4.14}, {"text": "And -- and a teenager -- teenagers must know that if you commit the worst crime, you will get the worst punishment that's available under the Constitution.", "start": 2568.824, "stop": 2577.764, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "And so, the symmetry here is that -- that Terrence Graham was the lucky one.", "start": 2577.764, "stop": 2582.901, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "It's not that Kuntrell Jackson was the unlucky one.", "start": 2582.901, "stop": 2585.368, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "This is a -- when you go into a place with a sawed-off shotgun, it's a dangerous activity; it's inherently dangerous.", "start": 2585.368, "stop": 2592.524, "duration": 7.16}, {"text": "And what was left out of the calculus a minute -- a few minutes ago was the fact that he could -- it's not just kill or intend to kill, but foresee what could happen.", "start": 2592.524, "stop": 2603.565, "duration": 11.04}, {"text": "And certainly the evidence in this case demonstrated that Kuntrell Jackson could foresee that at an armed robbery, someone could get hurt.", "start": 2603.565, "stop": 2612.185, "duration": 8.62}, {"text": "And that's what the law punishes, is the result.", "start": 2612.185, "stop": 2616.122, "duration": 3.94}, {"text": "If there are no further questions--", "start": 2616.122, "stop": 2619.591, "duration": 3.47}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 2619.591, "stop": 2621.007, "duration": 1.42}, {"text": "Mr. Stevenson, you have 8 minutes remaining.", "start": 2621.007, "stop": 2623.393, "duration": 2.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Bryan A. Stevenson", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just -- just a few points.", "start": 2623.393, "stop": 2627.097, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "Justice Kennedy, I just want to kind of remark, there is some literature out there about commutation in Arkansas.", "start": 2627.097, "stop": 2632.482, "duration": 5.38}, {"text": "And it was actually quite common up until 1980, and this case that my colleague referenced was prior to that date.", "start": 2632.482, "stop": 2638.905, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "But since then, it's been very uncommon.", "start": 2638.905, "stop": 2641.505, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "There's only been one commutation since 2007 with the current governor, and that was for a non-homicide offense.", "start": 2641.505, "stop": 2649.46, "duration": 7.95}, {"text": "I -- I also want to say, but just kind of consistent with my earlier argument, that this Court did strike down mandatory death sentences in Woodson v. North Carolina and Roberts v. Louisiana for many of the reasons that the Court has highlighted here that made that sentence unconstitutional and inappropriate.", "start": 2649.46, "stop": 2665.805, "duration": 16.34}, {"text": "And we think that in the same way, the Court could certainly do that here.", "start": 2665.805, "stop": 2669.607, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "But my final point is really to just say we are not suggesting that States should not be able to impose very harsh punishments and very severe sentences on even children who commit these kinds of violent crimes.", "start": 2669.607, "stop": 2682.948, "duration": 13.34}, {"text": "That's not our position.", "start": 2682.948, "stop": 2684.2, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "The State of Arkansas and the State of Alabama have parole boards in place.", "start": 2684.2, "stop": 2688.752, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "They can even impose sentences that give them the authority to maintain control of the lives of these children for the rest of their natural lives.", "start": 2688.752, "stop": 2696.257, "duration": 7.51}, {"text": "What we are arguing is that they cannot do so with no hope of release, that that would be incompatible with child status.", "start": 2696.257, "stop": 2704.013, "duration": 7.76}, {"text": "And that's the rule of Roper.", "start": 2704.013, "stop": 2705.763, "duration": 1.75}, {"text": "That's the logic of Roper and Graham.", "start": 2705.763, "stop": 2707.899, "duration": 2.14}, {"text": "It could be argued that every person is more than the worst thing they've ever done.", "start": 2707.899, "stop": 2712.467, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "And a policymaker and a decisionmaker might consider that in constructing what kind of sentences to impose and what kind of regime to create, and that's totally up to the legislatures.", "start": 2712.467, "stop": 2722.325, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "But what this Court has said is that children are uniquely more than their worst act.", "start": 2722.325, "stop": 2727.462, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "They are quintessentially children in a way that the Constitution requires that we respect their child status.", "start": 2727.462, "stop": 2735.732, "duration": 8.27}, {"text": "And our argument is simple.", "start": 2735.732, "stop": 2737.251, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "Our argument is that it would be unusual to recognize that in virtually every area of the law but when a crime is committed, to simply abandon it, to simply ignore it.", "start": 2737.251, "stop": 2747.357, "duration": 10.11}, {"text": "Roper and Graham teach us that we can't do that consistently with our Eighth Amendment prohibitions.", "start": 2747.357, "stop": 2752.761, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "And so, for that reason, it is unusual, and it's our judgment that it would be cruel to declare these children fit only to die in prison given what we now know about their status, about their development, and about their potential.", "start": 2752.761, "stop": 2766.685, "duration": 13.92}, {"text": "And for those reasons, we would ask this Court to reverse the lower court judgments and grant relief in this case, Jackson v. Arkansas.", "start": 2766.685, "stop": 2774.174, "duration": 7.49}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Stevenson, Mr. Holt.", "start": 2774.174, "stop": 2776.207, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 2776.207, "stop": 2777.126, "duration": 0.92}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Roberts Court", "arguedOn": "Mar 20, 2012", "petitioner": "Evan Miller", "respondent": "Alabama", "docket": "10-9646", "citation": "567 US _ (2012)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/567/10-9646", "lowerCourt": "Supreme Court of Alabama", "grantedOn": "Nov 7, 2011", "decidedOn": "Jun 25, 2012", "wikiData": {"title": "Miller v. Alabama", "Litigants": "Miller v. Alabama", "ArgueDate": "March 19", "ArgueYear": "2012", "DecideDate": "June 24", "DecideYear": "2012", "FullName": "Evan Miller, Petitioner v. Alabama; Kuntrell Jackson, Petitioner v. Ray Hobbs, Director, [[Arkansas Department of Correction]]", "USVol": "567", "USPage": "460", "ParallelCitations": "132 S. Ct. 2455; 183 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 407", "Docket": "10-9646", "Docket2": "10-9647", "Prior": "conviction affirmed sub nom. ''Miller v. State'', 2010 WL 2546422 (Ala. Crim. App. June 25, 2010); rehearing denied, and new decision published, 63 [[So.3d]] 676 (Ala. Crim. App. August 27, 2010); certiorari denied sub nom. ''Ex parte Miller'', unpub. n°1091663 (Ala. October 22, 2010); certiorari granted, 565 U. S. 1013 (2011)<br>", "onviction affirmed sub nom. ''Jackson v. State'', 359 Ark. 87, 194 S.W.3d 757 (2004); petition for habeas relief dismissed, unpub. n°cv-08-28-2 (Jefferson Cnty Cir. Ct.); affirmed, 2011 Ark. 49, 378 S. W. 3d 103 (2011); certiorari granted, 565 U. S. 1013 (2011)": "", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "", "SCOTUS": "2010-2016", "Majority": "Kagan", "JoinMajority": "Kennedy, Ginsburg, Breyer, Sotomayor", "Concurrence": "Breyer", "JoinConcurrence": "Sotomayor", "Dissent": "Roberts", "JoinDissent": "Scalia, Thomas, Alito", "Dissent2": "Thomas", "JoinDissent2": "Scalia", "Dissent3": "Alito", "JoinDissent3": "Scalia", "LawsApplied": "[[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. Amend. VIII]]"}}